{"title_page": "Force spectroscopy", "text_new": "'''Force spectroscopy''' is a set of techniques for the study of the interactions and the binding forces between individual molecules.<ref name=\"NeumanNagy2008\">{{cite journal |last1=Neuman |first1=Keir C |last2=Nagy |first2=Attila |title=Single-molecule force spectroscopy: optical tweezers, magnetic tweezers and atomic force microscopy |journal=Nature Methods |date=29 May 2008 |volume=5 |issue=6 |pages=491\u2013505 |doi=10.1038/nmeth.1218 |pmid=18511917 |pmc=3397402 }}</ref><ref name=\"HoffmannDougan2012\">{{cite journal |last1=Hoffmann |first1=Toni |last2=Dougan |first2=Lorna |title=Single molecule force spectroscopy using polyproteins |journal=Chemical Society Reviews |date=2012 |volume=41 |issue=14 |pages=4781\u201396 |doi=10.1039/c2cs35033e |pmid=22648310 }}</ref> These methods can be used to measure the mechanical properties of single [[polymer]] [[molecule]]s or [[proteins]], or individual [[chemical bond]]s. The name \"force [[spectroscopy]]\", although widely used in the scientific community, is somewhat misleading, because there is no true [[matter-radiation interaction]].<ref name=\"BizzarriCannistraro2012\">{{cite book|author1=Anna Rita Bizzarri|author2=Salvatore Cannistraro|title=Dynamic Force Spectroscopy and Biomolecular Recognition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Gl8yGoQNUcC&pg=PP1|date=25 January 2012|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|isbn=978-1-4398-6237-7|pages=1\u2013}}</ref>\n\nTechniques that can be used to perform force spectroscopy include [[atomic force microscopy]],<ref name=\"HoffmannDougan2012\" /> [[optical tweezers]],<ref name=Jagannathan2013>{{cite journal |last1=Jagannathan |first1=Bharat |last2=Marqusee |first2=Susan |title=Protein folding and unfolding under force |journal=Biopolymers |date=November 2013 |volume=99 |issue=11 |pages=860\u2013869 |doi=10.1002/bip.22321 |pmid=23784721 |pmc=4065244 }}</ref> [[magnetic tweezers]], acoustic force spectroscopy,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |last1=Sitters |first1=Gerrit |last2=Kamsma |first2=Douwe |last3=Thalhammer |first3=Gregor |last4=Ritsch-Marte |first4=Monika |last5=Peterman |first5=Erwin J G |last6=Wuite |first6=Gijs J L |title=Acoustic force spectroscopy |journal=Nature Methods |date=24 November 2014 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=47\u201350 |doi=10.1038/nmeth.3183 |pmid=25419961 }}</ref> microneedles,<ref name=\"KishinoYanagida1988\">{{cite journal |last1=Kishino |first1=Akiyoshi |last2=Yanagida |first2=Toshio |title=Force measurements by micromanipulation of a single actin filament by glass needles |journal=Nature |date=July 1988 |volume=334 |issue=6177 |pages=74\u201376 |doi=10.1038/334074a0 |pmid=3386748 |bibcode=1988Natur.334...74K }}</ref> and biomembranes.<ref name=\"EvansRitchie1995\">{{cite journal |last1=Evans |first1=E. |last2=Ritchie |first2=K. |last3=Merkel |first3=R. |title=Sensitive force technique to probe molecular adhesion and structural linkages at biological interfaces |journal=Biophysical Journal |date=June 1995 |volume=68 |issue=6 |pages=2580\u20132587 |doi=10.1016/S0006-3495(95)80441-8 |pmid=7647261 |bibcode=1995BpJ....68.2580E |pmc=1282168 }}</ref>\n\nForce spectroscopy measures the behavior of a molecule under stretching or torsional mechanical [[force]]. In this way a great deal has been learned in recent years about the mechanochemical coupling in the enzymes responsible for [[muscle]] contraction, transport in the [[cell (biology)|cell]], energy generation (F1-ATPase), [[DNA]] replication and transcription (polymerases), DNA unknotting and unwinding (topoisomerases and helicases).{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nAs a [[single-molecule]] technique, as opposed to typical [[statistical ensemble|ensemble]] spectroscopies, it allows a researcher to determine properties of the particular molecule under study. In particular, rare events such as conformational change, which are masked in an ensemble, may be observed.\n\n==Experimental techniques==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2014}}\nThere are many ways to accurately manipulate single molecules. Prominent among these are optical or magnetic tweezers, atomic-force-microscope (AFM) cantilevers and acoustic force spectroscopy.  In all of these techniques, a biomolecule, such as protein or DNA, or some other biopolymer has one end bound to a surface and the other to a force sensor.  The force sensor is usually a micrometre-sized bead or a cantilever, whose displacement can be measured to determine the force.\n\n===Atomic force microscope cantilevers===\nMolecules [[adsorption|adsorbed]] on a [[Interface (matter)|surface]] are picked up by a \nmicroscopic tip (nanometres wide) that is located on the end of an elastic cantilever.  In a  more sophisticated version of this experiment (Chemical Force Microscopy) the tips are covalently functionalized with the molecules of interest.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ott |first1=Wolfgang |last2=Jobst |first2=Markus A. |last3=Schoeler |first3=Constantin |last4=Gaub |first4=Hermann E. |last5=Nash |first5=Michael A. |title=Single-molecule force spectroscopy on polyproteins and receptor\u2013ligand complexes: The current toolbox |journal=Journal of Structural Biology |date=January 2017 |volume=197 |issue=1 |pages=3\u201312 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2016.02.011 |pmid=26873782 }}</ref> A [[piezoelectric]] controller then pulls up the cantilever.  If some force is acting on the elastic cantilever (for example because some molecule is being stretched between the surface and the tip), this will deflect upward (repulsive force) or downward (attractive force).  According to [[Hooke's law]], this deflection will be proportional to the force acting on the cantilever.  Deflection is measured by the position of a [[laser]] beam reflected by the cantilever. This kind of set-up can measure forces as low as 10 pN (10<sup>\u221211</sup> [[newton (unit)|N]]), the fundamental resolution limit is given by the cantilever's thermal [[noise]].\n\nThe so-called force curve is the graph of force (or more precisely, of cantilever deflection) versus the piezoelectric position on the Z axis. An ideal Hookean [[spring (device)|spring]], for example, would display a straight diagonal force curve.\nTypically, the force curves observed in the force spectroscopy experiments consist of a contact (diagonal) region where the probe contacts the sample surface, and a non-contact region where the probe is off the sample surface. When the restoring force of the cantilever exceeds tip-sample adhesion force the probe jumps out of contact, and the magnitude of this jump is often used as a measure of adhesion force or rupture force.  In general the rupture of a tip-surface bond is a stochastic process; therefore reliable quantification of the adhesion force requires taking multiple individual force curves. The histogram of the adhesion forces obtained in these multiple measurements provides the main data output for force spectroscopy measurement.\n\nIn biophysics, single-molecule force spectroscopy can be used to study the energy landscape underlying the interaction between two bio-molecules, like proteins. Here, one binding partner can be attached to a cantilever tip via a flexible linker molecule (PEG chain), while the other one is immobilized on a substrate surface. In a typical approach, the cantilever is repeatedly approached and retracted from the sample at a constant speed. In some cases, binding between the two partners will occur, which will become visible in the force curve, as the use of a flexible linker gives rise to a characteristic curve shape (see [[Worm-like chain]] model) distinct from adhesion. The collected rupture forces can then be analysed as a function of the bond loading rate. The resulting graph of the average rupture force as a function of the loading rate is called the ''force spectrum'' and forms the basic dataset for ''dynamic force spectroscopy''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bhushan |first1=Bharat |title=Springer handbook of nanotechnology |date=2017 |isbn=9783662543573 |oclc=1012104482 }}{{pn|date=October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite book |last1=Hinterdorfer |first1=Peter |last2=Van Oijen |first2=Antoine |title=Handbook of single-molecule biophysics |date=2009 |publisher=Springer |isbn=9780387764979 |oclc=534951120 }}{{pn|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the ideal case of a single sharp energy barrier for the tip-sample interactions the dynamic force spectrum will show a linear increase of the rupture force as function of a logarithm of the loading rate, as described by a model proposed by Bell et al.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bell |first1=G. |title=Models for the specific adhesion of cells to cells |journal=Science |date=12 May 1978 |volume=200 |issue=4342 |pages=618\u2013627 |doi=10.1126/science.347575 |pmid=347575 |bibcode=1978Sci...200..618B }}</ref>  Here, the slope of the rupture force spectrum is equal to the <math>\\frac{k_BT}{x_\\beta}</math>, where <math>x_\\beta</math> is the distance from the energy minimum to the transition state. So far, a number of theoretical models exist describing the relationship between loading rate and rupture force, based upon different assumptions and predicting distinct curve shapes.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Friddle | first1 = Raymond W. | last2 = Noy | first2 = Aleksandr | last3 = De Yoreo | first3 = James J. | year = 2012 | title = Interpreting the widespread nonlinear force spectra of intermolecular bonds | url = https://www.pnas.org/content/109/34/13573 | journal = PNAS | volume = 109 | issue = 34| pages = 13573\u201313578 }}</ref><ref>Rafayel Petrosyan, (March 2020) \"Unfolding force definition and the unified model for the mean unfolding force dependence on the loading rate\" J. Stat. Mech. 033201. https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1742-5468/ab6a05</ref>\n\nFor example, Ma X.,Gosai A. et al., utilized dynamic force spectroscopy along with molecular dynamics simulations to find out the binding force between thrombin, a blood coagulation protein, and its DNA aptamer.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ma |first1=Xiao |last2=Gosai |first2=Agnivo |last3=Balasubramanian |first3=Ganesh |last4=Shrotriya |first4=Pranav |title=Force spectroscopy of the thrombin-aptamer interaction: Comparison between AFM experiments and molecular dynamics simulations |journal=Applied Surface Science |date=May 2019 |volume=475 |pages=462\u2013472 |doi=10.1016/j.apsusc.2019.01.004 |bibcode=2019ApSS..475..462M }}</ref>\n\n=== Acoustic force spectroscopy ===\nA recently developed technique, acoustic force spectroscopy (AFS), allows the force manipulation of hundreds of single-molecules and single-cells in parallel, providing high experimental throughput.<ref name=\":0\" /> In this technique, a piezo element resonantly excites planar acoustic waves over a microfluidic chip. The generated acoustic waves are capable of exerting forces on microspheres with different density than the surrounding medium. Biomolecules, such as DNA, RNA or proteins, can be individually tethered between the microspheres and a surface and then probed by the acoustic forces exerted by the piezo sensor. Cells can be manipulated by the acoustic forces directly, or by using microspheres as handles.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sorkin |first1=Raya |last2=Bergamaschi |first2=Giulia |last3=Kamsma |first3=Douwe |last4=Brand |first4=Guy |last5=Dekel |first5=Elya |last6=Ofir-Birin |first6=Yifat |last7=Rudik |first7=Ariel |last8=Gironella |first8=Marta |last9=Ritort |first9=Felix |last10=Regev-Rudzki |first10=Neta |last11=Roos |first11=Wouter H. |last12=Wuite |first12=Gijs J. L. |last13=Discher |first13=Dennis |title=Probing cellular mechanics with acoustic force spectroscopy |journal=Molecular Biology of the Cell |date=8 August 2018 |volume=29 |issue=16 |pages=2005\u20132011 |doi=10.1091/mbc.E18-03-0154 |pmid=29927358 |pmc=6232971 }}</ref> With AFS devices it is possible to apply forces ranging from 0 to several hundreds of picoNewtons on hundreds of microspheres and obtain force-extension curves or histograms of rupture forces of many individual events in parallel.\n\n===Optical tweezers===\nAnother technique that has been gaining ground for single molecule experiments is the use of [[optical tweezers]] for applying mechanical forces on molecules. A strongly focused [[laser]] beam has the ability to catch and hold particles (of dielectric material) in a size range from nanometers to micrometers. The trapping action of optical tweezers results from the dipole or optical gradient force on the dielectric sphere. The technique of using a focused laser beam as an atom trap was first applied in 1984 at Bell laboratories. Until then experiments had been carried out using oppositely directed lasers as a means to trap particles. Later experiments, at the same project at Bell laboratories and others since, showed damage-free manipulation on cells using an infrared laser. Thus, the ground was made for biological experiments with optical trapping.\n\nEach technique has its own advantages and disadvantages. For example, AFM cantilevers, can measure angstrom-scale, millisecond events and forces larger than 10 pN. While glass microfibers cannot achieve such fine spatial and temporal resolution, they can measure piconewton forces. Optical tweezers allow the measurement of piconewton forces and nanometer displacements which is an ideal range for many biological experiments. Magnetic tweezers can measure femtonewton forces, and additionally they can also be used to apply torsion. AFS devices allow the statistical analysis of the mechanical properties of biological systems by applying picoNewton forces to hundreds of individual particles in parallel, with sub-millisecond response time.\n\n==Applications==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2014|talk=Anchor}}\nCommon applications of force spectroscopy are measurements of [[polymer]] [[elasticity (physics)|elasticity]], especially biopolymers such as [[RNA]] and [[DNA]]. Another [[biophysics|biophysical]] application of polymer force spectroscopy is on [[protein]] unfolding.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jagannathan |first1=B. |last2=Elms |first2=P. J. |last3=Bustamante |first3=C. |last4=Marqusee |first4=S. |title=Direct observation of a force-induced switch in the anisotropic mechanical unfolding pathway of a protein |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=4 September 2012 |volume=109 |issue=44 |pages=17820\u201317825 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1201800109 |pmid=22949695 |pmc=3497811 |bibcode=2012PNAS..10917820J }}</ref> Modular proteins can be adsorbed to a [[gold]] or (more rarely) [[mica]] [[Interface (matter)|surface]] and then stretched. The sequential unfolding of modules is observed as a very characteristic sawtooth pattern of the force vs elongation graph; every tooth corresponds to the unfolding of a single protein module (apart from the last that is generally the detachment of the protein molecule from the tip). Much information about protein elasticity and protein unfolding can be obtained by this technique. Many proteins in the living [[cell (biology)|cell]] must face mechanical stress.\n\nMoreover, force spectroscopy can be used to investigate the enzymatic activity of proteins involved in DNA [[DNA replication|replication]], [[Transcription (biology)|transcription]], organization and [[DNA repair|repair]]. This is achieved by measuring the position of a bead attached to a DNA-protein complex stalled on a DNA tether that has one end attached to a surface, while keeping the force constant. This technique has been used, for example, to study transcription elongation inhibition by Klebsidin and Acinetodin.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Metelev |first1=Mikhail |last2=Arseniev |first2=Anatolii |last3=Bushin |first3=Leah B. |last4=Kuznedelov |first4=Konstantin |last5=Artamonova |first5=Tatiana O. |last6=Kondratenko |first6=Ruslan |last7=Khodorkovskii |first7=Mikhail |last8=Seyedsayamdost |first8=Mohammad R. |last9=Severinov |first9=Konstantin |title=Acinetodin and Klebsidin, RNA Polymerase Targeting Lasso Peptides Produced by Human Isolates of Acinetobacter gyllenbergii and Klebsiella pneumoniae |journal=ACS Chemical Biology |date=3 February 2017 |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=814\u2013824 |doi=10.1021/acschembio.6b01154 |pmid=28106375 }}</ref>\n\nThe other main application of force spectroscopy is the study of [[mechanical resistance]] of chemical bonds. In this case, generally the tip is functionalized with a ligand that binds to another molecule bound to the surface. The tip is pushed on the surface, allowing for contact between the two molecules, and then retracted until the newly formed bond breaks up. The force at which the bond breaks up is measured. Since mechanical breaking is a kinetic, [[stochastic process]], the breaking force is not an absolute parameter, but it is a function of both temperature and pulling speed. Low temperatures and high pulling speeds correspond to higher breaking forces. By careful analysis of the breaking force at various pulling speeds, it is possible to map the [[energy]] landscape of the chemical bond under mechanical force. This is leading to interesting results in the study of [[antibody]]-[[antigen]], protein-protein, protein-living cell interaction and [[catch bonds]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schoeler |first1=Constantin |last2=Malinowska |first2=Klara H. |last3=Bernardi |first3=Rafael C. |last4=Milles |first4=Lukas F. |last5=Jobst |first5=Markus A. |last6=Durner |first6=Ellis |last7=Ott |first7=Wolfgang |last8=Fried |first8=Daniel B. |last9=Bayer |first9=Edward A. |last10=Schulten |first10=Klaus |last11=Gaub |first11=Hermann E. |last12=Nash |first12=Michael A. |title=Ultrastable cellulosome-adhesion complex tightens under load |journal=Nature Communications |date=8 December 2014 |volume=5 |issue=1 |pages=5635 |doi=10.1038/ncomms6635 |pmid=25482395 |pmc=4266597 |bibcode=2014NatCo...5E5635S }}</ref>\n\nRecently this technique has been used in [[cell biology]] to measure the aggregative [[stochastic]] forces created by [[motor proteins]] that influence the motion of particles within the cytoplasm. In this, way force spectrum microscopy may be used better to understand the many cellular processes that require the motion of particles within cytoplasm.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Guo |first1=Ming |last2=Ehrlicher |first2=Allen\u00a0J. |last3=Jensen |first3=Mikkel\u00a0H. |last4=Renz |first4=Malte |last5=Moore |first5=Jeffrey\u00a0R. |last6=Goldman |first6=Robert\u00a0D. |last7=Lippincott-Schwartz |first7=Jennifer |last8=Mackintosh |first8=Frederick\u00a0C. |last9=Weitz |first9=David\u00a0A. |title=Probing the Stochastic, Motor-Driven Properties of the Cytoplasm Using Force Spectrum Microscopy |journal=Cell |date=August 2014 |volume=158 |issue=4 |pages=822\u2013832 |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2014.06.051 |pmid=25126787 |pmc=4183065 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Hugel | first1 = T | last2 = Seitz | first2 = M | year = 2001 | title = The study of molecular interactions by AFM force spectroscopy | url = | journal = Macromol Rapid Commun | volume = 22 | issue = 13| pages = 989\u20131016 | doi=10.1002/1521-3927(20010901)22:13<989::aid-marc989>3.0.co;2-d}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Janshoff | first1 = A | last2 = Neitzert | first2 = M | last3 = Oberdorfer | first3 = Y | last4 = Fuchs | first4 = H | year = 2000 | title = Force spectroscopy of molecular systems-single molecule spectroscopy of polymers and biomolecules | url = | journal = Angew Chem Int Ed | volume = 39 | issue = 18| pages = 3212\u20133237 | doi=10.1002/1521-3773(20000915)39:18<3212::aid-anie3212>3.0.co;2-x}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Oesterhelt | first1 = F. | last2 = Rief | first2 = M. | last3 = Gaub | first3 = H. E. | year = 1999 | title =  Single molecule force spectroscopy by AFM indicates helical structure of poly(ethylene-glycol) in water| url = | journal = New J. Phys. | volume = 1 | issue = 6| page = 1 | doi = 10.1088/1367-2630/1/1/006 | bibcode = 1999NJPh....1....6O }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Rief | first1 = M. | last2 = Grubmueller | first2 = H. | year = 2001 | title = Force spectroscopy of single biomolecules | url = | journal = ChemPhysChem | volume = 57 | issue = | pages = 255\u2013261 }}\n*Smith, S.; Cui, Y.; Bustamante, C. Science (Washington, D.C.) 1996; 271:795.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Zhang | first1 = WK | last2 = Zhang | first2 = X | year = 2003 | title = Single molecule mechanochemistry of macromolecules | url = | journal = Prog Polym Sci | volume = 28 | issue = 8| pages = 1271\u20131295 | doi=10.1016/s0079-6700(03)00046-7}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Jagannathan | first1 = B. | last2 = Marqusee | first2 = S. | year = 2013 | title = Protein Folding and Unfolding under Force | journal = Biopolymers | volume = 99 | issue = 11| pages = 860\u2013869 | doi=10.1002/bip.22321 | pmid=23784721 | pmc=4065244}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Force Spectroscopy}}\n[[Category:Spectroscopy]]\n[[Category:Scanning probe microscopy]]\n", "text_old": "'''Force spectroscopy''' is a set of techniques for the study of the interactions and the binding forces between individual molecules.<ref name=\"NeumanNagy2008\">{{cite journal |last1=Neuman |first1=Keir C |last2=Nagy |first2=Attila |title=Single-molecule force spectroscopy: optical tweezers, magnetic tweezers and atomic force microscopy |journal=Nature Methods |date=29 May 2008 |volume=5 |issue=6 |pages=491\u2013505 |doi=10.1038/nmeth.1218 |pmid=18511917 |pmc=3397402 }}</ref><ref name=\"HoffmannDougan2012\">{{cite journal |last1=Hoffmann |first1=Toni |last2=Dougan |first2=Lorna |title=Single molecule force spectroscopy using polyproteins |journal=Chemical Society Reviews |date=2012 |volume=41 |issue=14 |pages=4781\u201396 |doi=10.1039/c2cs35033e |pmid=22648310 }}</ref> These methods can be used to measure the mechanical properties of single [[polymer]] [[molecule]]s or [[proteins]], or individual [[chemical bond]]s. The name \"force [[spectroscopy]]\", although widely used in the scientific community, is somewhat misleading, because there is no true [[matter-radiation interaction]].<ref name=\"BizzarriCannistraro2012\">{{cite book|author1=Anna Rita Bizzarri|author2=Salvatore Cannistraro|title=Dynamic Force Spectroscopy and Biomolecular Recognition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Gl8yGoQNUcC&pg=PP1|date=25 January 2012|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|isbn=978-1-4398-6237-7|pages=1\u2013}}</ref>\n\nTechniques that can be used to perform force spectroscopy include [[atomic force microscopy]],<ref name=\"HoffmannDougan2012\" /> [[optical tweezers]],<ref name=Jagannathan2013>{{cite journal |last1=Jagannathan |first1=Bharat |last2=Marqusee |first2=Susan |title=Protein folding and unfolding under force |journal=Biopolymers |date=November 2013 |volume=99 |issue=11 |pages=860\u2013869 |doi=10.1002/bip.22321 |pmid=23784721 |pmc=4065244 }}</ref> [[magnetic tweezers]], acoustic force spectroscopy,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |last1=Sitters |first1=Gerrit |last2=Kamsma |first2=Douwe |last3=Thalhammer |first3=Gregor |last4=Ritsch-Marte |first4=Monika |last5=Peterman |first5=Erwin J G |last6=Wuite |first6=Gijs J L |title=Acoustic force spectroscopy |journal=Nature Methods |date=24 November 2014 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=47\u201350 |doi=10.1038/nmeth.3183 |pmid=25419961 }}</ref> microneedles,<ref name=\"KishinoYanagida1988\">{{cite journal |last1=Kishino |first1=Akiyoshi |last2=Yanagida |first2=Toshio |title=Force measurements by micromanipulation of a single actin filament by glass needles |journal=Nature |date=July 1988 |volume=334 |issue=6177 |pages=74\u201376 |doi=10.1038/334074a0 |pmid=3386748 |bibcode=1988Natur.334...74K }}</ref> and biomembranes.<ref name=\"EvansRitchie1995\">{{cite journal |last1=Evans |first1=E. |last2=Ritchie |first2=K. |last3=Merkel |first3=R. |title=Sensitive force technique to probe molecular adhesion and structural linkages at biological interfaces |journal=Biophysical Journal |date=June 1995 |volume=68 |issue=6 |pages=2580\u20132587 |doi=10.1016/S0006-3495(95)80441-8 |pmid=7647261 |bibcode=1995BpJ....68.2580E |pmc=1282168 }}</ref>\n\nForce spectroscopy measures the behavior of a molecule under stretching or torsional mechanical [[force]]. In this way a great deal has been learned in recent years about the mechanochemical coupling in the enzymes responsible for [[muscle]] contraction, transport in the [[cell (biology)|cell]], energy generation (F1-ATPase), [[DNA]] replication and transcription (polymerases), DNA unknotting and unwinding (topoisomerases and helicases).{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nAs a [[single-molecule]] technique, as opposed to typical [[statistical ensemble|ensemble]] spectroscopies, it allows a researcher to determine properties of the particular molecule under study. In particular, rare events such as conformational change, which are masked in an ensemble, may be observed.\n\n==Experimental techniques==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2014}}\nThere are many ways to accurately manipulate single molecules. Prominent among these are optical or magnetic tweezers, atomic-force-microscope (AFM) cantilevers and acoustic force spectroscopy.  In all of these techniques, a biomolecule, such as protein or DNA, or some other biopolymer has one end bound to a surface and the other to a force sensor.  The force sensor is usually a micrometre-sized bead or a cantilever, whose displacement can be measured to determine the force.\n\n===Atomic force microscope cantilevers===\nMolecules [[adsorption|adsorbed]] on a [[Interface (matter)|surface]] are picked up by a \nmicroscopic tip (nanometres wide) that is located on the end of an elastic cantilever.  In a  more sophisticated version of this experiment (Chemical Force Microscopy) the tips are covalently functionalized with the molecules of interest.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ott |first1=Wolfgang |last2=Jobst |first2=Markus A. |last3=Schoeler |first3=Constantin |last4=Gaub |first4=Hermann E. |last5=Nash |first5=Michael A. |title=Single-molecule force spectroscopy on polyproteins and receptor\u2013ligand complexes: The current toolbox |journal=Journal of Structural Biology |date=January 2017 |volume=197 |issue=1 |pages=3\u201312 |doi=10.1016/j.jsb.2016.02.011 |pmid=26873782 }}</ref> A [[piezoelectric]] controller then pulls up the cantilever.  If some force is acting on the elastic cantilever (for example because some molecule is being stretched between the surface and the tip), this will deflect upward (repulsive force) or downward (attractive force).  According to [[Hooke's law]], this deflection will be proportional to the force acting on the cantilever.  Deflection is measured by the position of a [[laser]] beam reflected by the cantilever. This kind of set-up can measure forces as low as 10 pN (10<sup>\u221211</sup> [[newton (unit)|N]]), the fundamental resolution limit is given by the cantilever's thermal [[noise]].\n\nThe so-called force curve is the graph of force (or more precisely, of cantilever deflection) versus the piezoelectric position on the Z axis. An ideal Hookean [[spring (device)|spring]], for example, would display a straight diagonal force curve.\nTypically, the force curves observed in the force spectroscopy experiments consist of a contact (diagonal) region where the probe contacts the sample surface, and a non-contact region where the probe is off the sample surface. When the restoring force of the cantilever exceeds tip-sample adhesion force the probe jumps out of contact, and the magnitude of this jump is often used as a measure of adhesion force or rupture force.  In general the rupture of a tip-surface bond is a stochastic process; therefore reliable quantification of the adhesion force requires taking multiple individual force curves. The histogram of the adhesion forces obtained in these multiple measurements provides the main data output for force spectroscopy measurement.\n\nIn biophysics, single-molecule force spectroscopy can be used to study the energy landscape underlying the interaction between two bio-molecules, like proteins. Here, one binding partner can be attached to a cantilever tip via a flexible linker molecule (PEG chain), while the other one is immobilized on a substrate surface. In a typical approach, the cantilever is repeatedly approached and retracted from the sample at a constant speed. In some cases, binding between the two partners will occur, which will become visible in the force curve, as the use of a flexible linker gives rise to a characteristic curve shape (see [[Worm-like chain]] model) distinct from adhesion. The collected rupture forces can then be analysed as a function of the bond loading rate. The resulting graph of the average rupture force as a function of the loading rate is called the ''force spectrum'' and forms the basic dataset for ''dynamic force spectroscopy''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bhushan |first1=Bharat |title=Springer handbook of nanotechnology |date=2017 |isbn=9783662543573 |oclc=1012104482 }}{{pn|date=October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite book |last1=Hinterdorfer |first1=Peter |last2=Van Oijen |first2=Antoine |title=Handbook of single-molecule biophysics |date=2009 |publisher=Springer |isbn=9780387764979 |oclc=534951120 }}{{pn|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the ideal case of a single sharp energy barrier for the tip-sample interactions the dynamic force spectrum will show a linear increase of the rupture force as function of a logarithm of the loading rate, as described by a model proposed by Bell et al.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bell |first1=G. |title=Models for the specific adhesion of cells to cells |journal=Science |date=12 May 1978 |volume=200 |issue=4342 |pages=618\u2013627 |doi=10.1126/science.347575 |pmid=347575 |bibcode=1978Sci...200..618B }}</ref>  Here, the slope of the rupture force spectrum is equal to the <math>\\frac{k_BT}{x_\\beta}</math>, where <math>x_\\beta</math> is the distance from the energy minimum to the transition state. So far, a number of theoretical models exist describing the relationship between loading rate and rupture force, based upon different assumptions and predicting distinct curve shapes.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Raymond W. Friddle, Aleksandr Noy, and James J. De Yoreo, (August 2012) \"Interpreting the widespread nonlinear force spectra of intermolecular bonds\". PNAS 109 (34): 13573-13578. https://www.pnas.org/content/109/34/13573</ref><ref>Rafayel Petrosyan, (March 2020) \"Unfolding force definition and the unified model for the mean unfolding force dependence on the loading rate\" J. Stat. Mech. 033201. https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1742-5468/ab6a05</ref>\n\nFor example, Ma X.,Gosai A. et al., utilized dynamic force spectroscopy along with molecular dynamics simulations to find out the binding force between thrombin, a blood coagulation protein, and its DNA aptamer.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ma |first1=Xiao |last2=Gosai |first2=Agnivo |last3=Balasubramanian |first3=Ganesh |last4=Shrotriya |first4=Pranav |title=Force spectroscopy of the thrombin-aptamer interaction: Comparison between AFM experiments and molecular dynamics simulations |journal=Applied Surface Science |date=May 2019 |volume=475 |pages=462\u2013472 |doi=10.1016/j.apsusc.2019.01.004 |bibcode=2019ApSS..475..462M }}</ref>\n\n=== Acoustic force spectroscopy ===\nA recently developed technique, acoustic force spectroscopy (AFS), allows the force manipulation of hundreds of single-molecules and single-cells in parallel, providing high experimental throughput.<ref name=\":0\" /> In this technique, a piezo element resonantly excites planar acoustic waves over a microfluidic chip. The generated acoustic waves are capable of exerting forces on microspheres with different density than the surrounding medium. Biomolecules, such as DNA, RNA or proteins, can be individually tethered between the microspheres and a surface and then probed by the acoustic forces exerted by the piezo sensor. Cells can be manipulated by the acoustic forces directly, or by using microspheres as handles.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sorkin |first1=Raya |last2=Bergamaschi |first2=Giulia |last3=Kamsma |first3=Douwe |last4=Brand |first4=Guy |last5=Dekel |first5=Elya |last6=Ofir-Birin |first6=Yifat |last7=Rudik |first7=Ariel |last8=Gironella |first8=Marta |last9=Ritort |first9=Felix |last10=Regev-Rudzki |first10=Neta |last11=Roos |first11=Wouter H. |last12=Wuite |first12=Gijs J. L. |last13=Discher |first13=Dennis |title=Probing cellular mechanics with acoustic force spectroscopy |journal=Molecular Biology of the Cell |date=8 August 2018 |volume=29 |issue=16 |pages=2005\u20132011 |doi=10.1091/mbc.E18-03-0154 |pmid=29927358 }}</ref> With AFS devices it is possible to apply forces ranging from 0 to several hundreds of picoNewtons on hundreds of microspheres and obtain force-extension curves or histograms of rupture forces of many individual events in parallel.\n\n===Optical tweezers===\nAnother technique that has been gaining ground for single molecule experiments is the use of [[optical tweezers]] for applying mechanical forces on molecules. A strongly focused [[laser]] beam has the ability to catch and hold particles (of dielectric material) in a size range from nanometers to micrometers. The trapping action of optical tweezers results from the dipole or optical gradient force on the dielectric sphere. The technique of using a focused laser beam as an atom trap was first applied in 1984 at Bell laboratories. Until then experiments had been carried out using oppositely directed lasers as a means to trap particles. Later experiments, at the same project at Bell laboratories and others since, showed damage-free manipulation on cells using an infrared laser. Thus, the ground was made for biological experiments with optical trapping.\n\nEach technique has its own advantages and disadvantages. For example, AFM cantilevers, can measure angstrom-scale, millisecond events and forces larger than 10 pN. While glass microfibers cannot achieve such fine spatial and temporal resolution, they can measure piconewton forces. Optical tweezers allow the measurement of piconewton forces and nanometer displacements which is an ideal range for many biological experiments. Magnetic tweezers can measure femtonewton forces, and additionally they can also be used to apply torsion. AFS devices allow the statistical analysis of the mechanical properties of biological systems by applying picoNewton forces to hundreds of individual particles in parallel, with sub-millisecond response time.\n\n==Applications==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2014|talk=Anchor}}\nCommon applications of force spectroscopy are measurements of [[polymer]] [[elasticity (physics)|elasticity]], especially biopolymers such as [[RNA]] and [[DNA]]. Another [[biophysics|biophysical]] application of polymer force spectroscopy is on [[protein]] unfolding.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jagannathan |first1=B. |last2=Elms |first2=P. J. |last3=Bustamante |first3=C. |last4=Marqusee |first4=S. |title=Direct observation of a force-induced switch in the anisotropic mechanical unfolding pathway of a protein |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=4 September 2012 |volume=109 |issue=44 |pages=17820\u201317825 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1201800109 |pmid=22949695 |pmc=3497811 |bibcode=2012PNAS..10917820J }}</ref> Modular proteins can be adsorbed to a [[gold]] or (more rarely) [[mica]] [[Interface (matter)|surface]] and then stretched. The sequential unfolding of modules is observed as a very characteristic sawtooth pattern of the force vs elongation graph; every tooth corresponds to the unfolding of a single protein module (apart from the last that is generally the detachment of the protein molecule from the tip). Much information about protein elasticity and protein unfolding can be obtained by this technique. Many proteins in the living [[cell (biology)|cell]] must face mechanical stress.\n\nMoreover, force spectroscopy can be used to investigate the enzymatic activity of proteins involved in DNA [[DNA replication|replication]], [[Transcription (biology)|transcription]], organization and [[DNA repair|repair]]. This is achieved by measuring the position of a bead attached to a DNA-protein complex stalled on a DNA tether that has one end attached to a surface, while keeping the force constant. This technique has been used, for example, to study transcription elongation inhibition by Klebsidin and Acinetodin.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Metelev |first1=Mikhail |last2=Arseniev |first2=Anatolii |last3=Bushin |first3=Leah B. |last4=Kuznedelov |first4=Konstantin |last5=Artamonova |first5=Tatiana O. |last6=Kondratenko |first6=Ruslan |last7=Khodorkovskii |first7=Mikhail |last8=Seyedsayamdost |first8=Mohammad R. |last9=Severinov |first9=Konstantin |title=Acinetodin and Klebsidin, RNA Polymerase Targeting Lasso Peptides Produced by Human Isolates of Acinetobacter gyllenbergii and Klebsiella pneumoniae |journal=ACS Chemical Biology |date=3 February 2017 |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=814\u2013824 |doi=10.1021/acschembio.6b01154 |pmid=28106375 }}</ref>\n\nThe other main application of force spectroscopy is the study of [[mechanical resistance]] of chemical bonds. In this case, generally the tip is functionalized with a ligand that binds to another molecule bound to the surface. The tip is pushed on the surface, allowing for contact between the two molecules, and then retracted until the newly formed bond breaks up. The force at which the bond breaks up is measured. Since mechanical breaking is a kinetic, [[stochastic process]], the breaking force is not an absolute parameter, but it is a function of both temperature and pulling speed. Low temperatures and high pulling speeds correspond to higher breaking forces. By careful analysis of the breaking force at various pulling speeds, it is possible to map the [[energy]] landscape of the chemical bond under mechanical force. This is leading to interesting results in the study of [[antibody]]-[[antigen]], protein-protein, protein-living cell interaction and [[catch bonds]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schoeler |first1=Constantin |last2=Malinowska |first2=Klara H. |last3=Bernardi |first3=Rafael C. |last4=Milles |first4=Lukas F. |last5=Jobst |first5=Markus A. |last6=Durner |first6=Ellis |last7=Ott |first7=Wolfgang |last8=Fried |first8=Daniel B. |last9=Bayer |first9=Edward A. |last10=Schulten |first10=Klaus |last11=Gaub |first11=Hermann E. |last12=Nash |first12=Michael A. |title=Ultrastable cellulosome-adhesion complex tightens under load |journal=Nature Communications |date=8 December 2014 |volume=5 |issue=1 |pages=5635 |doi=10.1038/ncomms6635 |pmid=25482395 |pmc=4266597 |bibcode=2014NatCo...5E5635S }}</ref>\n\nRecently this technique has been used in [[cell biology]] to measure the aggregative [[stochastic]] forces created by [[motor proteins]] that influence the motion of particles within the cytoplasm. In this, way force spectrum microscopy may be used better to understand the many cellular processes that require the motion of particles within cytoplasm.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Guo |first1=Ming |last2=Ehrlicher |first2=Allen\u00a0J. |last3=Jensen |first3=Mikkel\u00a0H. |last4=Renz |first4=Malte |last5=Moore |first5=Jeffrey\u00a0R. |last6=Goldman |first6=Robert\u00a0D. |last7=Lippincott-Schwartz |first7=Jennifer |last8=Mackintosh |first8=Frederick\u00a0C. |last9=Weitz |first9=David\u00a0A. |title=Probing the Stochastic, Motor-Driven Properties of the Cytoplasm Using Force Spectrum Microscopy |journal=Cell |date=August 2014 |volume=158 |issue=4 |pages=822\u2013832 |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2014.06.051 |pmid=25126787 |pmc=4183065 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Hugel | first1 = T | last2 = Seitz | first2 = M | year = 2001 | title = The study of molecular interactions by AFM force spectroscopy | url = | journal = Macromol Rapid Commun | volume = 22 | issue = 13| pages = 989\u20131016 | doi=10.1002/1521-3927(20010901)22:13<989::aid-marc989>3.0.co;2-d}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Janshoff | first1 = A | last2 = Neitzert | first2 = M | last3 = Oberdorfer | first3 = Y | last4 = Fuchs | first4 = H | year = 2000 | title = Force spectroscopy of molecular systems-single molecule spectroscopy of polymers and biomolecules | url = | journal = Angew Chem Int Ed | volume = 39 | issue = 18| pages = 3212\u20133237 | doi=10.1002/1521-3773(20000915)39:18<3212::aid-anie3212>3.0.co;2-x}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Oesterhelt | first1 = F. | last2 = Rief | first2 = M. | last3 = Gaub | first3 = H. E. | year = 1999 | title =  Single molecule force spectroscopy by AFM indicates helical structure of poly(ethylene-glycol) in water| url = | journal = New J. Phys. | volume = 1 | issue = 6| page = 1 | doi = 10.1088/1367-2630/1/1/006 | bibcode = 1999NJPh....1....6O }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Rief | first1 = M. | last2 = Grubmueller | first2 = H. | year = 2001 | title = Force spectroscopy of single biomolecules | url = | journal = ChemPhysChem | volume = 57 | issue = | pages = 255\u2013261 }}\n*Smith, S.; Cui, Y.; Bustamante, C. Science (Washington, D.C.) 1996; 271:795.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Zhang | first1 = WK | last2 = Zhang | first2 = X | year = 2003 | title = Single molecule mechanochemistry of macromolecules | url = | journal = Prog Polym Sci | volume = 28 | issue = 8| pages = 1271\u20131295 | doi=10.1016/s0079-6700(03)00046-7}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Jagannathan | first1 = B. | last2 = Marqusee | first2 = S. | year = 2013 | title = Protein Folding and Unfolding under Force | journal = Biopolymers | volume = 99 | issue = 11| pages = 860\u2013869 | doi=10.1002/bip.22321 | pmid=23784721 | pmc=4065244}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Force Spectroscopy}}\n[[Category:Spectroscopy]]\n[[Category:Scanning probe microscopy]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, added 1 PMC, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Force_spectroscopy"}
{"title_page": "Luge at the 1964 Winter Olympics", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Luge at the Olympics}}\n{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Luge\n|games = 1964 Winter\n|image = Luge pictogram.svg\n|image_size = 100px\n|venue = [[Olympic Sliding Centre Innsbruck]]\n|dates = 30 January \u2013 4 February\n|competitors = 68\n|nations = 12\n|next = [[Luge at the 1968 Winter Olympics|1968]]\n}}\n{{Luge at the 1964 Winter Olympics}}\n'''[[Luge]] at the [[1964 Winter Olympics]]''' consisted of three events at [[Olympic Sliding Centre Innsbruck]].  The competition took place between 30 January and 4 February 1964.<ref name=OfficialReport>{{cite web\n| title       = Offizieller Bericht der IX. Olympischen Winterspiele Innsbruck 1964\n| url         = http://library.la84.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1964/orw1964.pdf\n| publisher   = LA84 Foundation\n| work          = Austrian Federal Publishing House for Instruction, Science and Art, Vienna and Munich\n| year        = 1964\n| accessdate  = 20 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThis was the first appearance of Luge in the Winter Olympics. It was originally scheduled to be added in 1960, but as there was no venue built for it in [[1960 Winter Olympics|Squaw Valley]], the sport's debut came in 1964.<ref name=SportsReference>{{cite web\n| title       = Luge at the 1964 Winter Games\n| url         = https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1964/LUG/\n| publisher   = Sports-Reference.com\n| accessdate  = 20 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Medal summary==\n\n===Medal table===\n<ref name=OfficialReport />\n{{Medals table\n | caption        = \n | host           = \n | flag_template  = flagIOC\n | event          = 1964 Winter\n | team           = \n | gold_EUA = 2 | silver_EUA = 2 | bronze_EUA = 1\n | gold_AUT = 1 | silver_AUT = 1 | bronze_AUT = 1\n | gold_ITA = 0 | silver_ITA = 0 | bronze_ITA = 1\n}}\n\n\nGermany won five of the nine medals available, including two gold medals.\n\n===Events===\n<ref name=OfficialReport />\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event|columns=2}}\n|-\n| Men's singles <br>{{DetailsLink|Luge at the 1964 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's singles}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Thomas K\u00f6hler]]|EUA|1964 Winter}} || 3:26.77\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Klaus-Michael Bonsack]]|EUA|1964 Winter}} || 3:27.04\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Hans Plenk]]|EUA|1964 Winter}} || 3:30.15\n|-\n| Women's singles <br>{{DetailsLink|Luge at the 1964 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's singles}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Ortrun Enderlein]]|EUA|1964 Winter}} || 3:24.67\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Ilse Geisler]]|EUA|1964 Winter}} || 3:27.42\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Leni Thurner]]|AUT|1964 Winter}} || 3:29.06\n|-\n| Doubles <br>{{DetailsLink|Luge at the 1964 Winter Olympics \u2013 Doubles}}\n|{{flagIOCteam|AUT|1964 Winter}}<br/> [[Josef Feistmantl]] <br/> [[Manfred Stengl]] || 1:41.62\n|{{flagIOCteam|AUT|1964 Winter}}<br/> [[Reinhold Senn]] <br/> [[Helmut Thaler]] || 1:41.91\n|{{flagIOCteam|ITA|1964 Winter}}<br/> [[Walter Au\u00dfendorfer]] <br/> [[Sigisfredo Mair]] || 1:42.87\n|}\n\n==Participating NOCs==\n<ref name=OfficialReport/>\n\nTwelve nations participated in Luge at the Innsbruck Games.\n\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-1-of-2}}\n* {{flagIOC|ARG|1964 Winter|1}}\n* {{flagIOC|AUT|1964 Winter|9}}\n* {{flagIOC|CAN|1964 Winter|1}}\n* {{flagIOC|GBR|1964 Winter|2}}\n* {{flagIOC|EUA|1964 Winter|9}}\n* {{flagIOC|ITA|1964 Winter|7}}\n{{col-2-of-2}}\n* {{flagIOC|LIE|1964 Winter|3}}\n* {{flagIOC|NOR|1964 Winter|4}}\n* {{flagIOC|POL|1964 Winter|8}}\n* {{flagIOC|SUI|1964 Winter|9}}\n* {{flagIOC|TCH|1964 Winter|6}}\n* {{flagIOC|USA|1964 Winter|9}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1964/LUG/ Sports-Reference - 1964 Olympics - Luge]\n\n{{Events at the 1964 Winter Olympics}}\n{{Luge at the Winter Olympics}}\n\n[[Category:Luge at the Winter Olympics|1964]]\n[[Category:1964 Winter Olympics events]]\n[[Category:Luge at the 1964 Winter Olympics| ]]\n[[Category:1964 in luge]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Luge at the Olympics}}\n{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Luge\n|games = 1964 Winter\n|image = Luge pictogram.svg\n|image_size = 100px\n|venue = [[Olympic Sliding Centre Innsbruck]]\n|dates = 30 January - 4 February\n|competitors = 68\n|nations = 12\n|next = [[Luge at the 1968 Winter Olympics|1968]]\n}}\n{{Luge at the 1964 Winter Olympics}}\n'''[[Luge]] at the [[1964 Winter Olympics]]''' consisted of three events at [[Olympic Sliding Centre Innsbruck]].  The competition took place between January 30 and February 4, 1964.<ref name=OfficialReport>{{cite web\n| title       = Offizieller Bericht der IX. Olympischen Winterspiele Innsbruck 1964\n| url         = http://library.la84.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1964/orw1964.pdf\n| publisher   = LA84 Foundation\n| work          = Austrian Federal Publishing House for Instruction, Science and Art, Vienna and Munich\n| year        = 1964\n| accessdate  = January 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThis was the first appearance of Luge in the Winter Olympics. It was originally scheduled to be added in 1960, but as there was no venue built for it in [[1960 Winter Olympics|Squaw Valley]], the sport's debut came in 1964.<ref name=SportsReference>{{cite web\n| title       = Luge at the 1964 Winter Games\n| url         = https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1964/LUG/\n| publisher   = Sports-Reference.com\n| accessdate  = January 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Medal summary==\n\n===Medal table===\n<ref name=OfficialReport />\n{{Medals table\n | caption        = \n | host           = \n | flag_template  = flagIOC\n | event          = 1964 Winter\n | team           = \n | gold_EUA = 2 | silver_EUA = 2 | bronze_EUA = 1\n | gold_AUT = 1 | silver_AUT = 1 | bronze_AUT = 1\n | gold_ITA = 0 | silver_ITA = 0 | bronze_ITA = 1\n}}\n\n\nGermany won five of the nine medals available, including two gold medals.\n\n===Events===\n<ref name=OfficialReport />\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event|columns=2}}\n|-\n| Men's singles <br>{{De