gs]]\n[[Category:1500s paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings by Andrea Mantegna]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Royal Collection of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Military art]]\n[[Category:Hampton Court Palace]]\n[[Category:Gonzaga art collection]]\n[[Category:Dogs in art]]\n[[Category:Horses in art]]\n[[Category:Musical instruments in art]]\n[[Category:Elephants in art]]\n[[Category:Paintings depicting Julius Caesar]]\n", "name_user": "Nizolan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1960s restoration:-space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triumphs_of_Caesar_(Mantegna)"}
{"title_page": "Population Matters", "text_new": "{{short description|UK-based charity}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Population Matters\n| image = \n| image_size = 150px\n| type = {{plainlist|\n*[[Environmental charity]]\n*[[Sustainability organisation]]\n*[[Advocacy group]]\n*[[Think tank]]}}\n| tax_id = <!-- or | vat_id = -->\n| registration_id = \n| formerly = Optimum Population Trust\n| founded_date = {{start date and age|1991}}\n| founder = David Willey\n| location = [[United Kingdom]]\n| origins = \n| key_people = {{plainlist|\n*[[Jonathon Porritt]] ([[President (corporate title)|president]])\n*[[Sara Parkin]] ([[Chairman|chair]]) }}\n| area_served = \n| product = \n| focus = [[Family planning|Promotion of smaller families]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/smaller-families/|title=Smaller families|author=|date=|work=populationmatters.org}}</ref> and [[sustainable consumption]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/what-else|title=Consume mindfully|author=|date=|work=populationmatters.org}}</ref>\n| mission = \n| method = Campaigning, education, lobbying and research\n| revenue = \n| expenses = \n| endowment = \n| num_volunteers = \n| num_employees = \n| num_members = \n| subsid = \n| owner = \n| homepage = {{URL|populationmatters.org/}}\n}}\n'''Population Matters''', formerly known as the '''Optimum Population Trust''', is a UK-based charity that addresses population size and its effects on [[Sustainability|environmental sustainability]]. It considers population growth as a major contributor to [[environmental degradation]], [[biodiversity loss]], [[resource depletion]] and [[climate change]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/population-growth-climate-change/|title=Does Population Growth Impact Climate Change?|website=Scientific American|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2019/02/28/climate-change-and-population-growth-are-making-the-worlds-water-woes-more-urgent|title=Climate change and population growth are making the world's water woes more urgent|date=2019-02-28|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-04-05|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> The group promotes ethical, choice-based solutions through lobbying, campaigning and awareness-raising.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/solutions|title=Solutions|date=2018-09-11|website=Population Matters {{!}} Sustainable World Population {{!}} Every Choice Counts|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==History and background==\nPopulation Matters was launched as the Optimum Population Trust following a meeting on 24 July 1991 by the late David Willey and others concerned about population numbers and sustainability. They were impelled to act by the failure of United Kingdom governments to respond to [[population growth]] and threats to sustainability.\n\nThe Optimum Population Trust prepared analyses and lobbied on issues affected by population growth. It was granted charitable status on 9 May 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityFramework.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1114109&SubsidiaryNumber=0|title=Charity framework|website=Charity Commission|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> Population Matters was adopted as its new name in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/governance|title=Governance|date=2018-09-13|website=Population Matters|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Views and aims ==\nPopulation Matters highlights how rapid human population growth has fueled the destruction of nature and natural resource depletion.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The charity promotes positive, voluntary measures to achieve a sustainable human population size that enables everyone to have a decent quality of life while safeguarding our natural environment.\n\nThe United Nations projects that global population size will reach 9.7&nbsp;billion in the year 2050 and 10.9 in 2100,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://population.un.org/wpp/Publications/Files/WPP2019_10KeyFindings.pdf|title=World Population Prospects 2019 (Key findings)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which illustrates the urgency of the matter, according to the organisation.\n\n=== Vision ===\nPopulation Matters' vision<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/about-us|title=About us|date=2018-09-18|website=Population Matters {{!}} Every Choice Counts {{!}} Sustainable World Population|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> is of a future in which our population co-exists in harmony with nature and prospers on a healthy planet, to the benefit of all.\n\n===Mission===\nPopulation Matters' mission is to drive positive, large-scale action through fostering choices that help achieve a sustainable human population and regenerate our environment. \n\n=== Solutions ===\nPopulation Matters promotes five solutions to slow and ultimately reverse population growth:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/solutions|title=Solutions|date=2018-09-11|website=Population Matters {{!}} Every Choice Counts {{!}} Sustainable World Population|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n* Achieve global gender equality\n* Remove all barriers to modern family planning\n* Quality education for all\n* End poverty\n* Encourage small family size\n\nIn addition, recognising the disproportionately large environmental footprint of wealthy nations, the charity calls for reducing consumption in high-income countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/what-else|title=What else can I do?|date=2018-09-13|website=Population Matters {{!}} Every Choice Counts {{!}} Sustainable World Population|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nPopulation Matters campaigns to stabilise population at a sustainable level through encouraging a culture shift towards smaller family sizes worldwide and improving funding for women's empowerment and family planning in lower income countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meetup.com/Central-London-Humanists/events/61135812/|title=Central London Humanists|website=Meetup|access-date=2016-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2011/oct/23/why-population-growth-costs-the-earth-roger|title=Why current population growth is costing us the Earth |last=Martin|first=Roger|date=2011-10-23|website=the Guardian|access-date=2016-06-02}}</ref> Over the years, the organisation has supported various campaigns, including [[Caroline Lucas]]' Bill to make Personal, Social, Health and Economic education (''[[Personal, Social and Health Education|PSHE]]'') a statutory requirement in state-funded schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carolinelucas.com/latest/pshe-briefing-for-mps|title=PSHE briefing for MPs |first=Caroline |last=Lucas |access-date=2016-06-02}}</ref> It also informs the public on overpopulation and positive solutions through its communications, events and outreach activities. Finally, the charity commissions research to examine some issues in depth, for example, analysing the latest UN population projections, or exploring the impacts of UK population growth on biodiversity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/what-we-do|title=What we do|last=|first=|date=|website=Population Matters|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> \n\nPopulation Matters publishes the Journal of Population and Sustainability, an open access, peer-reviewed, interdisciplinary journal exploring all aspects of the relationship between human numbers and environmental issues.\n\nThe charity runs Empower to Plan, a crowdfunding' project that offers members of the public the opportunity to donate directly towards family planning and women's empowerment projects around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.populationmatters.org/empower-to-plan/|title=Empower to Plan|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref> This project superseded the carbon offsetting project called [[PopOffsets]].\n\n== Organisational structure ==\nPopulation Matters consists of patrons, an advisory council, a board, a team of staff, volunteers and members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/our-team|title=Our team - Population Matters|website=Population Matters|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> It relies on members and donors for its funding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/governance|title=Governance|date=2018-09-13|website=Population Matters|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Patrons ===\nPopulation Matters' patrons include prominent public figures such as [[David Attenborough|Sir David Attenborough]], [[Chris Packham]], [[Jane Goodall|Dr Jane Goodall]], [[Leilani Munter|Leilani M\u00fcnter]], [[Jonathon Porritt]], [[Partha Dasgupta|Sir Partha Dasgupta]], [[Paul R. Ehrlich|Professor Paul Ehrlich]], [[Lionel Shriver]] and [[John Guillebaud|Professor John Guillebaud]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.populationmatters.org/about/people-and-story/patrons/|title=Patrons - Population Matters|website=Population Matters|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-06-09}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nIn 2015, Population Matters was criticized for a blog post disagreeing with an [[Amnesty International]] call on the UK and other EU countries to \"significantly increase the number of resettlement and humanitarian admission places for refugees from Syria\" while saying that these \"countries should continue to support migrants from the Syrian civil war and other conflicts in the countries adjacent to those conflicts\".<ref name=\":0\" /> The organization subsequently confirmed that this had never been official Population Matters policy and had been repudiated and withdrawn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/past-policies|title=Population Matters\u2019 past policies|date=2020-01-31|website=Population Matters {{!}} Every Choice Counts {{!}} Sustainable World Population|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> The Optimum Population Trust had called for numerically balanced or \"zero-net\" migration to the UK, but did not continue to support this policy as Population Matters. In 2015, Population Matters advocated stopping child benefit and tax credits for third and subsequent children.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/ourkingdom/adam-ramsay/charity-which-campaigned-to-ban-syrian-refugees-from-britain|title=The charity which campaigned to ban Syrian refugees from Britain|date=2015-09-23|website=openDemocracy|access-date=2016-06-09}}</ref> In 2017, the organization stopped advocating for specific policy changes, replacing them with a call for a Sustainable Population Policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/campaigns/sustainable-population-policy|title=Sustainable population policy |publisher=Population Matters|access-date=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Environment}}\n{{colbegin}}\n*[[Futures studies]]\n*[[List of countries by population]]\n*[[List of countries by population growth rate]]\n*[[List of population concern organizations]]\n*[[List of sovereign states and dependent territories by birth rate]]\n*[[List of sovereign states and dependent territories by population density]]\n*[[Optimum population]]\n*[[Over-consumption]]\n*[[Overexploitation]]\n*[[Political demography]]\n*[[Population ageing]]\n*[[Population density]]\n*[[Population pyramid]]\n*[[Risks to civilization, humans and planet Earth]]\n*[[Tragedy of the commons]]\n*[[World population]]\n*[[Zero population growth]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.populationmatters.org Official website]\n\n{{population}}\n{{Human impact on the environment}}\n{{Population country lists}}\n{{sustainability}}\n{{biological organisation}}\n{{Extinction}}\n\n[[Category:Advocates of women's reproductive rights]]\n[[Category:Charities based in England]]\n[[Category:Conservation organizations]]\n[[Category:Environmental organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Human overpopulation think tanks]]\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in England]]\n[[Category:Political and economic think tanks]]\n[[Category:Political and economic think tanks based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Population concern advocacy groups]]\n[[Category:Population research organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|UK-based charity}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Population Matters\n| image = \n| image_size = 150px\n| type = {{plainlist|\n*[[Environmental charity]]\n*[[Sustainability organisation]]\n*[[Advocacy group]]\n*[[Think tank]]}}\n| tax_id = <!-- or | vat_id = -->\n| registration_id = \n| formerly = Optimum Population Trust\n| founded_date = {{start date and age|1991}}\n| founder = David Willey\n| location = [[United Kingdom]]\n| origins = \n| key_people = {{plainlist|\n*[[Jonathon Porritt]] ([[President (corporate title)|president]])\n*[[Sara Parkin]] ([[Chairman|chair]]) }}\n| area_served = \n| product = \n| focus = [[Family planning|Promotion of smaller families]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/smaller-families/|title=Smaller families|author=|date=|work=populationmatters.org}}</ref> and [[sustainable consumption]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/what-else|title=Consume mindfully|author=|date=|work=populationmatters.org}}</ref>\n| mission = \n| method = Campaigning, education, lobbying and research\n| revenue = \n| expenses = \n| endowment = \n| num_volunteers = \n| num_employees = \n| num_members = \n| subsid = \n| owner = \n| homepage = {{URL|populationmatters.org/}}\n}}\n'''Population Matters''', formerly known as the '''Optimum Population Trust''', is a UK-based charity that addresses population size and its effects on [[Sustainability|environmental sustainability]]. It considers population growth as a major contributor to [[environmental degradation]], [[biodiversity loss]], [[resource depletion]] and [[climate change]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/population-growth-climate-change/|title=Does Population Growth Impact Climate Change?|website=Scientific American|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2019/02/28/climate-change-and-population-growth-are-making-the-worlds-water-woes-more-urgent|title=Climate change and population growth are making the world's water woes more urgent|date=2019-02-28|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-04-05|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> The group promotes ethical, choice-based solutions through lobbying, campaigning and awareness-raising.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/solutions|title=Solutions|date=2018-09-11|website=Population Matters {{!}} Sustainable World Population {{!}} Every Choice Counts|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==History and background==\nPopulation Matters was launched as the Optimum Population Trust following a meeting on 24 July 1991 by the late David Willey and others concerned about population numbers and sustainability. They were impelled to act by the failure of United Kingdom governments to respond to [[population growth]] and threats to sustainability.\n\nThe Optimum Population Trust prepared analyses and lobbied on issues affected by population growth. It was granted charitable status on 9 May 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityFramework.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1114109&SubsidiaryNumber=0|title=Charity framework|website=Charity Commission|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref> Population Matters was adopted as its new name in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/governance|title=Governance|date=2018-09-13|website=Population Matters|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Views and aims ==\nPopulation Matters highlights how rapid human population growth has fueled the destruction of nature and natural resource depletion.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The charity promotes positive, voluntary measures to achieve a sustainable human population size that enables everyone to have a decent quality of life while safeguarding our natural environment.\n\nThe United Nations projects that global population size will reach 9.7&nbsp;billion in the year 2050 and 10.9 in 2100,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://population.un.org/wpp/Publications/Files/WPP2019_10KeyFindings.pdf|title=World Population Prospects 2019 (Key findings)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which illustrates the urgency of the matter, according to the organisation.\n\n=== '''Vision''' ===\nPopulation Matters' vision<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/about-us|title=About us|date=2018-09-18|website=Population Matters {{!}} Every Choice Counts {{!}} Sustainable World Population|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> is of a future in which our population co-exists in harmony with nature and prospers on a healthy planet, to the benefit of all.\n\n===Mission===\nPopulation Matters' mission is to drive positive, large-scale action through fostering choices that help achieve a sustainable human population and regenerate our environment. \n\n=== Solutions ===\nPopulation Matters promotes five solutions to slow and ultimately reverse population growth:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/solutions|title=Solutions|date=2018-09-11|website=Population Matters {{!}} Every Choice Counts {{!}} Sustainable World Population|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n* Achieve global gender equality\n* Remove all barriers to modern family planning\n* Quality education for all\n* End poverty\n* Encourage small family size\n\nIn addition, recognising the disproportionately large environmental footprint of wealthy nations, the charity calls for reducing consumption in high-income countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/what-else|title=What else can I do?|date=2018-09-13|website=Population Matters {{!}} Every Choice Counts {{!}} Sustainable World Population|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nPopulation Matters campaigns to stabilise population at a sustainable level through encouraging a culture shift towards smaller family sizes worldwide and improving funding for women's empowerment and family planning in lower income countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meetup.com/Central-London-Humanists/events/61135812/|title=Central London Humanists|website=Meetup|access-date=2016-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2011/oct/23/why-population-growth-costs-the-earth-roger|title=Why current population growth is costing us the Earth |last=Martin|first=Roger|date=2011-10-23|website=the Guardian|access-date=2016-06-02}}</ref> Over the years, the organisation has supported various campaigns, including [[Caroline Lucas]]' Bill to make Personal, Social, Health and Economic education (''[[Personal, Social and Health Education|PSHE]]'') a statutory requirement in state-funded schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carolinelucas.com/latest/pshe-briefing-for-mps|title=PSHE briefing for MPs |first=Caroline |last=Lucas |access-date=2016-06-02}}</ref> It also informs the public on overpopulation and positive solutions through its communications, events and outreach activities. Finally, the charity commissions research to examine some issues in depth, for example, analysing the latest UN population projections, or exploring the impacts of UK population growth on biodiversity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/what-we-do|title=What we do|last=|first=|date=|website=Population Matters|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> \n\nPopulation Matters publishes the Journal of Population and Sustainability, an open access, peer-reviewed, interdisciplinary journal exploring all aspects of the relationship between human numbers and environmental issues.\n\nThe charity runs Empower to Plan, a crowdfunding' project that offers members of the public the opportunity to donate directly towards family planning and women's empowerment projects around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.populationmatters.org/empower-to-plan/|title=Empower to Plan|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref> This project superseded the carbon offsetting project called [[PopOffsets]].\n\n== Organisational structure ==\nPopulation Matters consists of patrons, an advisory council, a board, a team of staff, volunteers and members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/our-team|title=Our team - Population Matters|website=Population Matters|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> It relies on members and donors for its funding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/governance|title=Governance|date=2018-09-13|website=Population Matters|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Patrons ===\nPopulation Matters' patrons include prominent public figures such as [[David Attenborough|Sir David Attenborough]], [[Chris Packham]], [[Jane Goodall|Dr Jane Goodall]], [[Leilani Munter|Leilani M\u00fcnter]], [[Jonathon Porritt]], [[Partha Dasgupta|Sir Partha Dasgupta]], [[Paul R. Ehrlich|Professor Paul Ehrlich]], [[Lionel Shriver]] and [[John Guillebaud|Professor John Guillebaud]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.populationmatters.org/about/people-and-story/patrons/|title=Patrons - Population Matters|website=Population Matters|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-06-09}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nIn 2015, Population Matters was criticized for a blog post disagreeing with an [[Amnesty International]] call on the UK and other EU countries to \"significantly increase the number of resettlement and humanitarian admission places for refugees from Syria\" while saying that these \"countries should continue to support migrants from the Syrian civil war and other conflicts in the countries adjacent to those conflicts\".<ref name=\":0\" /> The organization subsequently confirmed that this had never been official Population Matters policy and had been repudiated and withdrawn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/past-policies|title=Population Matters\u2019 past policies|date=2020-01-31|website=Population Matters {{!}} Every Choice Counts {{!}} Sustainable World Population|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> The Optimum Population Trust had called for numerically balanced or \"zero-net\" migration to the UK, but did not continue to support this policy as Population Matters. In 2015, Population Matters advocated stopping child benefit and tax credits for third and subsequent children.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/ourkingdom/adam-ramsay/charity-which-campaigned-to-ban-syrian-refugees-from-britain|title=The charity which campaigned to ban Syrian refugees from Britain|date=2015-09-23|website=openDemocracy|access-date=2016-06-09}}</ref> In 2017, the organization stopped advocating for specific policy changes, replacing them with a call for a Sustainable Population Policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://populationmatters.org/campaigns/sustainable-population-policy|title=Sustainable population policy |publisher=Population Matters|access-date=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Environment}}\n{{colbegin}}\n*[[Futures studies]]\n*[[List of countries by population]]\n*[[List of countries by population growth rate]]\n*[[List of population concern organizations]]\n*[[List of sovereign states and dependent territories by birth rate]]\n*[[List of sovereign states and dependent territories by population density]]\n*[[Optimum population]]\n*[[Over-consumption]]\n*[[Overexploitation]]\n*[[Political demography]]\n*[[Population ageing]]\n*[[Population density]]\n*[[Population pyramid]]\n*[[Risks to civilization, humans and planet Earth]]\n*[[Tragedy of the commons]]\n*[[World population]]\n*[[Zero population growth]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.populationmatters.org Official website]\n\n{{population}}\n{{Human impact on the environment}}\n{{Population country lists}}\n{{sustainability}}\n{{biological organisation}}\n{{Extinction}}\n\n[[Category:Advocates of women's reproductive rights]]\n[[Category:Charities based in England]]\n[[Category:Conservation organizations]]\n[[Category:Environmental organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Human overpopulation think tanks]]\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in England]]\n[[Category:Political and economic think tanks]]\n[[Category:Political and economic think tanks based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Population concern advocacy groups]]\n[[Category:Population research organizations]]\n", "name_user": "EtheyB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Formatting standardisation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Population_Matters"}
{"title_page": "Government of Bangladesh", "text_new": "{{short description|National government of Bangladesh}}\n{{About|governing body|political system in [[Bangladesh]] |Politics of Bangladesh}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox executive government\n| government_name  = The People's Republic of Bangladesh\n| nativename       = {{lang|bn|\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0}}\n| border           = <!-- for clarification, options are \"devolved\" (for UK use), \"federal\", \"central\" -->\n| image            = Government Seal of Bangladesh.svg\n| caption          = [[Government Seal of Bangladesh|Official Seal of The Government of Bangladesh]]\n| date_established = {{Start date|1971|04|17|df=y}} ([[Provisional Government of Bangladesh|1st Government]])\n| date_dissolved   =\n| state            = <!-- polity governed -->\n| polity           = <!-- if polity governed is not a state (e.g. subdivision of a state) -->\n| country          = [[Bangladesh]]\n| address          = [[Bangladesh Secretariat]]\n| leader_title     = [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh]]\n| appointed        = [[President of Bangladesh]]\n| budget           = <!-- annual budget of the government -->\n| main_organ       = [[Cabinet of Bangladesh]] \n| ministries       =\n| responsible      = <!-- responsible to parliament/president/monarch? -->\n| url              = {{URL|http://www.bangladesh.gov.bd/}}\n\n}}\n{{Politics of Bangladesh}}\nThe '''Government of Bangladesh''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0}}) has three branches. These are the Executive branch, the Legislative branch and the Judicial branch. The Legislature of Bangladesh is [[Unicameralism|unicameral]]. Called the [[Sangsad|Jatiya Sangsad]] in Bengali, it is the parliament of Bangladesh. The [[Speaker of the Jatiya Sangsad|Speaker]] presides over meetings of the Jatiya Sangsad and conducts its business in an orderly fashion. The current Jatiya Sangsad contains 350 seats, including 50 seats reserved exclusively for women and 300 seats for elected members, which are apportioned on elected party position in the parliament. The [[2018 Bangladesh general election|Eleventh National Parliamentary Election]] was held on 30 December 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=New MPs take oath |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/new-mps-take-oath-6107 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=9 January 2014 |access-date=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205001041/http://www.thedailystar.net/new-mps-take-oath-6107 |archive-date=5 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The current speaker is [[Shirin Sharmin Chaudhury]], who is presiding over the eleventh Parliament. She is the first woman to have held this office. \n\nThe Executive is led by the [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|Prime Minister]], who selects all the remaining Ministers. The Prime Minister and the other most senior Ministers belong to the supreme decision-making committee, known as the [[Cabinet of Bangladesh|Cabinet]]. The current Prime Minister is [[Sheikh Hasina]], leader of the [[Bangladesh Awami League]], who was appointed by the [[President of Bangladesh|President]] on 6 January 2009 following the [[2008 Bangladeshi general election|General Election]] on 29 December 2008. Bangladesh Awami League led by her, and its Grand Alliance (a total of 14 parties) won two-thirds majority in the elections. Numerically, the party controls 230 seats out of 299.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/7803785.stm \"Hasina wins Bangladesh landslide\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216215840/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/7803785.stm |date=16 February 2009 }}, BBC</ref>\n\nThe judicial branch systematically contains an apex [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh|Supreme Court]], which is composed of the [[Bangladesh Supreme Court, Appellate Division|Appellate Division]] and the [[High Court Division]]. There are various levels of the judiciary in Bangladesh \u2013 different types of courts form a strict hierarchy of importance \u2013 District Courts, City Criminal Courts, Specialized Courts and Tribunals are all inferior to the Supreme Court. The [[Chief Justice of Bangladesh]] is the head of the judiciary and the Supreme Court. The present and the 22nd Chief Justice of Bangladesh is [[Syed Mahmud Hossain]]. He succeeded Justice Md. Abdul Wahhab Miah on 2 February 2018.\n\n==Head of state==\nThe [[President of Bangladesh|President]] is the [[Head of State]], a largely ceremonial post. The real power is held by the [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|Prime Minister]], who is the [[head of government]]. The president is elected by the legislature every five years and has normally limited powers that are substantially expanded during the tenure of a [[caretaker government]], mainly in controlling the transition to a new government. Bangladesh has instituted a unique system of transfer of power; at the end of the tenure of the government, power is handed over to members of a civil society for three months, who run the general elections and transfer the power to elected representatives. This system was first practiced in 1991 and adopted to the constitution in 1996.<ref name=\"amend13\">''14th Amendment'', Constitution of Bangladesh, 1996.</ref>\n\nAs head of the state, the president can grant pardon to a man sentenced to death penalty or lessen the punishment. In some cases, it also performs some legislative and judicial functions.\n\n==Executive branch==\n===Prime Minister===\nThe [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|prime minister]] is ceremonially appointed by the president, commanding the confidence of the majority of the MPs. The cabinet is composed of selected [[Government minister|ministers]].\nPrime minister exercise supreme power in Bangladesh.\n\n===Cabinet===\n{{main|Cabinet of Bangladesh}}\nThe executive administrates the country and executes the laws, passed by the legislature. It maintains the internal law and order in the country. It also maintains relationship with foreign countries. It works for defence, liberty and sovereignty of the country.\n\n===Agencies===\n{{main|Government agencies in Bangladesh}}\nThe executive calculates the income and expenditure of the government. It also performs various public welfare services such as; education, agriculture, establishment of industry, trade & commerce, land reform, tax and revenue collection. Beside this, it also accepts and implements various development projects.\n\n===Local Government===\n{{main|Local government in Bangladesh}}\nAt the local government level, the country is divided into [[Divisions of Bangladesh|divisions]], [[Districts of Bangladesh|districts]], subdistricts ([[Upazila]]), [[Union Councils of Bangladesh|unions]], and villages. The lowest level of local government representative are Local officials of union council those who are elected at the union level election. All larger administrative units are run by members of the civil service.\n\n==Legislative branch==\n{{main|Jatiya Sangsad}}\n[[File:National Assembly of Bangladesh (07).jpg|thumb|[[Parliament of Bangladesh]]]]\nThe legislature of Bangladesh is [[Unicameralism|unicameral]]. The 300 members are elected by [[universal suffrage]] at least every 5 years.  It consists of 350 members at present. There is universal suffrage for all citizens at the age of 18.\n\n\"On 16 May 2004, the [[Jatiya Sangsad]] (the National Parliament) passed the 14th constitutional amendment to reintroduce quotas for women (article 65). The number of seats in parliament is to be raised to 345, 45 (15%) of which will be reserved for women in the next parliament. The seats will be allocated to parties in proportion to their overall share of the vote. This quota system replaces the previous quota law which expired in 2001. Until 2001 a system of reserved seats for women was used, where 30 seats out of 330 were reserved to women (chosen by indirect election by the 300 directly elected MPs). This provision of guaranteeing women reserved seats expired in April 2001. This quota system was first introduced by the 1972 Constitution (originally providing for 15 reserved seats for women, out of 315 seats, for a period of 10 years). In 1978 a presidential proclamation enlarged the number of reserved seats to 30 and extended the period of reservation to 15 years from the date of promulgation of the constitution of the Republic in December 1972. The constitutional provision lapsed in 1987 and was re-incorporated in the constitution by an amendment in 1990 to be effective for 10 years from the first meeting of the legislature next elected. This provision also lapsed in 2001. The Parliament elected in October 2001 does not have reserved seats for women. Women's groups are lobbying for these seats to become directly elected positions and for the number of reserved seats to be increased.\"\n\nThe 10th Parliament had its first sitting on 25 January 2009 . Currently there are 350 members of the house of which 50 memberships are reserved for women.<ref>Bangladesh and Global Studies (NCTB)</ref>\n\n== Judicial branch ==\n{{main|Judiciary of Bangladesh}}\n[[File:Bangladesh Supreme Court.jpg|thumb|[[Supreme Court of Bangladesh]]]]\n\n===Supreme Court===\nThe highest [[judiciary]] body is the [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh|Supreme Court]]. Until recently, Chief Justice and judges were recommended by the Prime Minister and formally appointed by the President. Since 1991, political parties during their tenure in government have initiated the separation of the judiciary from control by the executive branch brought about by amendment of the [[Constitution of Bangladesh]] in 1975. The separation by presidential promulgation acts have signed and passed. Acts on the separation of Judiciary Administration, Remuneration, Pay and Leave, etc. have all been completed. The Supreme Court have now judiciary and administrative authority over all lower courts in the country.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Politics of Bangladesh]]\n\n==References==\n\n* [https://bdgovtjobs.com/ Bangladesh Government MPO institute New List www.bangladesh.gov.bd]\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bangladesh topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Government of}}\n{{Ministries of Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Bangladesh| ]]\n[[Category:Asian governments]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|National government of Bangladesh}}\n{{About|governing body|political system in [[Bangladesh]] |Politics of Bangladesh}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox executive government\n| government_name  = The People's Republic of Bangladesh\n| nativename       = {{lang|bn|\u0997\u09a3\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0}}\n| border           = <!-- for clarification, options are \"devolved\" (for UK use), \"federal\", \"central\" -->\n| image            = Government Seal of Bangladesh.svg\n| caption          = [[Government Seal of Bangladesh|Official Seal of The Government of Bangladesh]]\n| date_established = {{Start date|1971|04|17|df=y}} ([[Provisional Government of Bangladesh|1st Government]])\n| date_dissolved   =\n| state            = <!-- polity governed -->\n| polity           = <!-- if polity governed is not a state (e.g. subdivision of a state) -->\n| country          = [[Bangladesh]]\n| address          = [[Bangladesh Secretariat]]\n| leader_title     = [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh]]\n| appointed        = [[President of Bangladesh]]\n| budget           = <!-- annual budget of the government -->\n| main_organ       = [[Cabinet of Bangladesh]] \n| ministries       =\n| responsible      = <!-- responsible to parliament/president/monarch? -->\n| url              = {{URL|http://www.bangladesh.gov.bd/}}\n\n}}\n{{Politics of Bangladesh}}\nThe '''Government of Bangladesh''' ({{lang-bn|\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09b8\u09b0\u0995\u09be\u09b0}}) has three branches. These are the Executive branch, the Legislative branch and the Judicial branch. The Legislature of Bangladesh is [[Unicameralism|unicameral]]. Called the [[Sangsad|Jatiya Sangsad]] in Bengali, it is the parliament of Bangladesh. The [[Speaker of the Jatiya Sangsad|Speaker]] presides over meetings of the Jatiya Sangsad and conducts its business in an orderly fashion. The current Jatiya Sangsad contains 350 seats, including 50 seats reserved exclusively for women and 300 seats for elected members, which are apportioned on elected party position in the parliament. The [[2018 Bangladesh general election|Eleventh National Parliamentary Election]] was held on 30 December 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=New MPs take oath |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/new-mps-take-oath-6107 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=9 January 2014 |access-date=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205001041/http://www.thedailystar.net/new-mps-take-oath-6107 |archive-date=5 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The current speaker is [[Shirin Sharmin Chaudhury]], who is presiding over the eleventh Parliament. She is the first woman to have held this office. \n\nThe Executive is led by the [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|Prime Minister]], who selects all the remaining Ministers. The Prime Minister and the other most senior Ministers belong to the supreme decision-making committee, known as the [[Cabinet of Bangladesh|Cabinet]]. The current Prime Minister is [[Sheikh Hasina]], leader of the [[Bangladesh Awami League]], who was appointed by the [[President of Bangladesh|President]] on 6 January 2009 following the [[2008 Bangladeshi general election|General Election]] on 29 December 2008. Bangladesh Awami League led by her, and its Grand Alliance (a total of 14 parties) won two-thirds majority in the elections. Numerically, the party controls 230 seats out of 299.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/7803785.stm \"Hasina wins Bangladesh landslide\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216215840/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/7803785.stm |date=16 February 2009 }}, BBC</ref>\n\nThe judicial branch systematically contains an apex [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh|Supreme Court]], which is composed of the [[Bangladesh Supreme Court, Appellate Division|Appellate Division]] and the [[High Court Division]]. There are various levels of the judiciary in Bangladesh \u2013 different types of courts form a strict hierarchy of importance \u2013 District Courts, City Criminal Courts, Specialized Courts and Tribunals are all inferior to the Supreme Court. The [[Chief Justice of Bangladesh]] is the head of the judiciary and the Supreme Court. The present and the 22nd Chief Justice of Bangladesh is [[Syed Mahmud Hossain]]. He succeeded Justice Md. Abdul Wahhab Miah on 2 February 2018.\n\n==Head of state==\nThe [[President of Bangladesh|President]] is the [[Head of State]], a largely ceremonial post. The real power is held by the [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|Prime Minister]], who is the [[head of government]]. The president is elected by the legislature every five years and has normally limited powers that are substantially expanded during the tenure of a [[caretaker government]], mainly in controlling the transition to a new government. Bangladesh has instituted a unique system of transfer of power; at the end of the tenure of the government, power is handed over to members of a civil society for three months, who run the general elections and transfer the power to elected representatives. This system was first practiced in 1991 and adopted to the constitution in 1996.<ref name=\"amend13\">''14th Amendment'', Constitution of Bangladesh, 1996.</ref>\n\nAs head of the state, the president can grant pardon to a man sentenced to death penalty or lessen the punishment. In some cases, it also performs some legislative and judicial functions.\n\n==Executive branch==\n===Prime Minister===\nThe [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|prime minister]] is ceremonially appointed by the president, commanding the confidence of the majority of the MPs. The cabinet is composed of selected [[Government minister|ministers]].\nPrime minister exercise supreme power in Bangladesh.\n\n===Cabinet===\n{{main|Cabinet of Bangladesh}}\nThe executive administrates the country and executes the laws, passed by the legislature. It maintains the internal law and order in the country. It also maintains relationship with foreign countries. It works for defence, liberty and sovereignty of the country.\n\n===Agencies===\n{{main|Government agencies in Bangladesh}}\nThe executive calculates the income and expenditure of the government. It also performs various public welfare services such as; education, agriculture, establishment of industry, trade & commerce, land reform, tax and revenue collection. Beside this, it also accepts and implements various development projects.\n\n===Local Government===\n{{main|Local government in Bangladesh}}\nAt the local government level, the country is divided into [[Divisions of Bangladesh|divisions]], [[Districts of Bangladesh|districts]], subdistricts ([[Upazila]]), [[Union Councils of Bangladesh|unions]], and villages. The lowest level of local government representative are Local officials of union council those who are elected at the union level election. All larger administrative units are run by members of the civil service.\n\n==Legislative branch==\n{{main|Jatiya Sangsad}}\n[[File:National Assembly of Bangladesh (07).jpg|thumb|[[Parliament of Bangladesh]]]]\nThe legislature of Bangladesh is [[Unicameralism|unicameral]]. The 300 members are elected by [[universal suffrage]] at least every 5 years.  It consists of 350 members at present. There is universal suffrage for all citizens at the age of 18.\n\n\"On 16 May 2004, the [[Jatiya Sangsad]] (the National Parliament) passed the 14th constitutional amendment to reintroduce quotas for women (article 65). The number of seats in parliament is to be raised to 345, 45 (15%) of which will be reserved for women in the next parliament. The seats will be allocated to parties in proportion to their overall share of the vote. This quota system replaces the previous quota law which expired in 2001. Until 2001 a system of reserved seats for women was used, where 30 seats out of 330 were reserved to women (chosen by indirect election by the 300 directly elected MPs). This provision of guaranteeing women reserved seats expired in April 2001. This quota system was first introduced by the 1972 Constitution (originally providing for 15 reserved seats for women, out of 315 seats, for a period of 10 years). In 1978 a presidential proclamation enlarged the number of reserved seats to 30 and extended the period of reservation to 15 years from the date of promulgation of the constitution of the Republic in December 1972. The constitutional provision lapsed in 1987 and was re-incorporated in the constitution by an amendment in 1990 to be effective for 10 years from the first meeting of the legislature next elected. This provision also lapsed in 2001. The Parliament elected in October 2001 does not have reserved seats for women. Women's groups are lobbying for these seats to become directly elected positions and for the number of reserved seats to be increased.\"\n\nThe 10th Parliament had its first sitting on 25 January 2009 . Currently there are 350 members of the house of which 50 memberships are reserved for women.<ref>Bangladesh and Global Studies (NCTB)</ref>\n\n== Judicial branch ==\n{{main|Judiciary of Bangladesh}}\n[[File:Bangladesh Supreme Court.jpg|thumb|[[Supreme Court of Bangladesh]]]]\n\n===Supreme Court===\nThe highest [[judiciary]] body is the [[Supreme Court of Bangladesh|Supreme Court]]. Until recently, Chief Justice and judges were recommended by the Prime Minister and formally appointed by the President. Since 1991, political parties during their tenure in government have initiated the separation of the judiciary from control by the executive branch brought about by amendment of the [[Constitution of Bangladesh]] in 1975. The separation by presidential promulgation acts have signed and passed. Acts on the separation of Judiciary Administration, Remuneration, Pay and Leave, etc. have all been completed. The Supreme Court have now judiciary and administrative authority over all lower courts in the country.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Politics of Bangladesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bangladesh topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Government of}}\n{{Ministries of Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Bangladesh| ]]\n[[Category:Asian governments]]\n", "name_user": "Nunoticebd", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(a Few days ago has been publish new mpo institute list 2020 by the government of Bangladesh. its very important news for Bangladeshi Educated people.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_of_Bangladesh"}
{"title_page": "Taylor Townsend", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name = Taylor Townsend\n| fullname =\n| image = Townsend RG19 (29) (48199067157).jpg\n| caption = Townsend at the [[2019 French Open]]\n| country = {{USA}}\n| residence = [[Smyrna, Georgia]], United States\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1996|4|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], Illinois, United States\n| height = 1.70 m\n| turnedpro = December 2012\n| retired =\n| plays = Left-handed (two-handed backhand)\n| careerprizemoney = [[US$]] 2,164,921\n| coach = Donald Young Sr.\n| singlesrecord = {{tennis record|won=209|lost=128}}\n| singlestitles = 0\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 61 (July 16, 2018)\n| currentsinglesranking = No. 73 (March 16, 2020)\n| AustralianOpenresult = 2R ([[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2020]])\n| FrenchOpenresult = 3R ([[2014 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2014]])\n| Wimbledonresult = 2R ([[2018 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2018]], [[2019 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2019]])\n| USOpenresult = 4R ([[2019 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2019]])\n| doublesrecord = {{tennis record|won=158|lost=63}}\n| doublestitles = 1 \n| highestdoublesranking = No. 64 (March 20, 2017)\n| currentdoublesranking = No. 84 (March 9, 2020)\n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult= 3R ([[2019 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2019]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult= 2R ([[2018 French Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2018]])\n| WimbledonDoublesresult= 1R ([[2017 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|2017]])\n| USOpenDoublesresult= QF ([[2016 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2016]])\n| AustralianOpenMixedresult =\n| FrenchOpenMixedresult =\n| WimbledonMixedresult =\n| USOpenMixedresult = SF ([[2014 US Open \u2013 Mixed Doubles|2014]])\n| Team = yes\n| FedCupresult = 1\u20130\n| updated = 9 March 2020\n}}\n\n'''Taylor Townsend''' (born April 16, 1996) is an [[American people|American]] professional [[tennis]] player. She reached a career-best [[WTA Rankings|WTA]] ranking of No. 61 in July 2018.\n\nShe was named the ITF Junior World Champion in 2012 for finishing the year No. 1 in the girls' junior rankings, making her the first American to do so since 1982. In that year, she won the junior [[2012 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|Australian Open]] titles in both singles and doubles, and three out of the four junior grand slam doubles titles in total.\n\n==Early life and background==\nTaylor was born in [[Chicago]] to Devin and Sheila Townsend. Her parents are both high school administrators, and her mother used to work as a banker. Sheila played Division II tennis at [[Lincoln University (Missouri)|Lincoln University]] in Missouri. Taylor has an older sister, Symone, who played college tennis at [[Florida A&M]].<ref name=rush /><ref name=chicago />\n\nTownsend started playing tennis at the age of six, and was one of the first junior players to participate in the XS Tennis program run by [[Kamau Murray]].<ref name=\"first-murray\">{{cite web |title=The Open Interview: Kamau Murray |url=http://www.usopen.org/en_US/news/articles/2017-09-10/2017-09-10_the_open_interview_kamau_murray.html?chip=8 |website=US Open |accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref> Murray is better known for coaching [[Sloane Stephens]] to a grand slam title. When she was eight years old, she moved to Atlanta to continue training with [[Donald Young (tennis)|Donald Young]]'s father. Townsend's mother is a close friend of Donald Young Sr., as the two of them grew up together on the [[South Side of Chicago]], where they trained at the same tennis center. At age 14, Townsend moved to [[Boca Raton, Florida]], to join the USTA development program. When the USTA decided not to fund Townsend's expenses to compete at the [[2012 US Open (tennis)|2012 US Open]], Murray and XS Tennis organized a fundraiser to cover nearly $1000 of the cost of the trip. After that, Townsend split time training with Murray in Chicago and [[Zina Garrison]] in the [[Washington DC]] area. Since 2015, Donald Young Sr. has again served as her coach. Townsend tries to model her game after her tennis idol, [[Martina Navratilova]].<ref name=chicago>{{cite web|title=Tennis takes Taylor Townsend from Englewood to Paris|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-05-23/news/ct-taylor-townsend-tennis-met-0521-20140523_1_tennis-scholarship-college-scholarships-englewood|website=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=espnw>{{cite web|title=Townsend, Young share deep connection|url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/11005122/espnw-taylor-townsend-donald-young-share-deep-connection|website=espnW|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=huff>{{cite web|title= Teen Tennis Star's Success is a Powerful Argument Against Body-Shaming |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/29/taylor-townsend-french-open_n_5412657.html|date=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Junior career==\nTownsend won the [[2012 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|2012 Australian Open]] junior tournament at the age of 15 to become only the second American to ever win that title after [[Kim Kessaris]] in 1989. She also won the [[2012 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|doubles title]] at the same event to become first American to win both the singles and doubles titles at a junior Grand Slam event since [[Lindsay Davenport]] accomplished the feat at the [[1992 US Open (tennis)|1992 US Open]].<ref name=si /> A few months later, Townsend won the Easter Bowl to help complete her rise to No. 1 in the ITF junior rankings before the end of April.<ref>{{cite web|title=Florida Tennis Briefs: American Townsend Rises to No. 1 in the ITF World Junior Tennis Rankings|url=http://www.florida.usta.com/news/florida_tennis_briefs5_gainesville_jax_score_at_league_nationals_manzo_honored111/|website=USTA Florida|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Taylor Townsend (USA) Backhand.jpg|thumb|left|Townsend at [[2012 US Open (tennis)|2012 US Open]]]]\nTownsend continued her junior Grand Slam success in doubles that year by winning the [[2012 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Doubles|Junior Wimbledon]] title with [[Eugenie Bouchard]] and the [[2012 US Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|US Open]] title with [[Gabrielle Andrews]], with whom she also partnered at the Australian Open. The only Grand Slam that eluded Townsend was the [[French Open]], where she lost in the semifinals while partnering with Bouchard. Additionally, she was able to win the US Open title in spite of being asked to sit out that tournament by the [[USTA]] over fitness concerns.<ref name=wsj1 /> This was only the seventh year where a player or team was able to win three out of four Grand Slam doubles titles, with senior Grand Slam winners [[Victoria Azarenka]] and [[Sloane Stephens]] among the others to complete this task. Townsend finished the season as the No. 1 ranked junior in the world, for which she was named the 2012 ITF Junior World Champion. She became the first American girl to hold this honor since [[Gretchen Rush]] in 1982.<ref name=rush>{{cite web|title=Being Considered the Next Serena Is a Compliment and a Detriment|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/23/sports/tennis/taylor-townsend-americas-latest-tennis-prodigy-prepares-to-turn-pro.html|website=New York Times|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nTownsend continued to play on the junior tour in 2013 and reached another Grand Slam singles final at [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Singles|Wimbledon]], this time losing to [[Belinda Bencic]]. She also competed in the USTA Junior National Championship as the No. 4 seed and was knocked out in the semifinals by No. 2 [[Allie Kiick]].\n\n==Professional career==\n===Early years: WTA doubles final===\nTownsend entered her first professional-level tournament in October 2010 at the age of 14 and was able to win her first career match. She also played in the doubles event at the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|2011 US Open]] when she was 15 years old and reached the third round with her compatriot [[Jessica Pegula]]. She also received a wild card into the singles qualifying draw and defeated world No. 122 [[Arantxa Parra Santonja]] in the first round. The following year, Townsend requested another wild card into the [[2012 US Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|2012 US Open]] and was declined due to the USTA's concerns about Townsend's fitness. The USTA received [[Taylor Townsend (tennis)#2012 US Open controversy|widespread criticism]] for this decision.<ref name=si /><ref name=wsj1 /><ref name=davenport />\n\nTownsend made her [[WTA Tour]] debut in singles at the [[2013 BNP Paribas Open|2013 Indian Wells Masters]], where she defeated [[Lucie Hradeck\u00e1]] for her first tour-level match win. Her next WTA main draw appearance came at the [[2013 Citi Open]]. Although Townsend lost in singles, she also competed in the [[2013 Citi Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|doubles event]] with [[Genie Bouchard]], her doubles partner from their Wimbledon girls' doubles title the previous summer. The duo made it all the way to the final, the first career WTA final for either player.\n\n===2014: First Grand Slam match wins===\n[[File:Taylor Townsend (15142083560).jpg|thumb|Townsend at the [[2014 Toray Pan Pacific Open]]]]\nIn back-to-back weeks in the spring, Townsend played at two clay court events on the USTA pro circuit at [[2014 Boyd Tinsley Women's Clay Court Classic|Charlottesville]] and [[2014 Audi Melbourne Pro Tennis Classic|Indian Harbour Beach]]. She won both the singles and doubles titles at each of these events, her first such ITF titles. Townsend partnered with [[Asia Muhammad]] in doubles at both tournaments. With this success, she won the USTA wild card entry into the [[2014 French Open|French Open]].<ref>{{cite web|title=18-Year-Old Taylor Townsend Secures French Open Wild Card|url=http://www.tennisnow.com/Blogs/NET-POSTS/May-2014/18-Year-Old-Taylor-Townsend-Secures-French-Open-Wi|website=Tennis Now|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> Townsend made her Grand Slam singles debut at the [[2014 French Open|French Open]] ranked No. 205 in the world. She defeated fellow American No. 65 [[Vania King]] and then upset the top-ranked French woman No. 21 [[Aliz\u00e9 Cornet]] to advance to the third round, where she lost to No. 15 [[Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro]].<ref>{{cite web|title=American tennis discovers new star in 18-year-old Taylor Townsend|url=http://www.tennisworldusa.org/tennis/news/American_Tennis/18218/american-tennis-discovers-new-star-in-18yearold-taylor-townsend/|website=Tennis World USA|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> [[Sloane Stephens]] was the only other American woman to make it that far in the tournament.\n\nTownsend also received wild cards to make her main draw debuts at the last two grand slams of the year, [[2014 Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] and the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], but lost in the first round at each tournament. The latter loss was to [[Serena Williams]], who went on to win the title.\n\n===2015: Top 100 debut, and decline===\n[[File:Townsend RG15 (5) (19120333829).jpg|thumb|left|Townsend at the [[2015 French Open]]]]\nTownsend broke into the top 100 of the WTA rankings at the very start of the season after reaching the second round at the [[2015 ASB Classic|ASB Classic]] in Auckland. With a higher ranking, she gained direct entry into the [[2014 Australian Open|Australian Open]] and lost to [[Caroline Wozniacki]] in the first round. In February, she made her [[Fed Cup]] debut against [[Argentina Fed Cup team|Argentina]] and won her only match, a [[dead rubber]] where she was partnered with [[CoCo Vandeweghe]]. Townsend then fell out of the top 100 in April and began to struggle with her form, winning just two matches on the ITF circuit the rest of the year and none at the WTA Tour level. She finished the year ranked outside of the top 300.\n\n===2016: Resurgence, ITF doubles dominance===\nWith a lower ranking, Townsend returned to playing ITF events almost exclusively. Her decision to switch back to her childhood coach, Donald Young Sr. after the 2015 French Open eventually began to pay off as she regained her form in the spring.<ref name=SIyoung>{{cite web|title=Taylor Townsend goes back to the basics after injury, coaching change|url=https://www.si.com/tennis/2015/05/26/taylor-townsend-french-open-ankle-injury-coaching-change|website=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> In April, she repeated her feat from 2014 of winning both the singles and doubles titles at [[2016 Boyd Tinsley Women's Clay Court Classic|Charlottesville]]. This again helped her win the French Open Wild Card Challenge. After partnering with Asia Muhammad just once in 2015, the previously successful doubles team recombined to win five ITF doubles titles by the end of April, including back-to-back-to-back clay court titles at Pelham, [[2016 Hardee's Pro Classic|Dothan]], and Charlottesville. Townsend returned to the Top 200 by May and got back to No. 154 after winning her first round match at the [[2016 French Open|French Open]]. From there, her ranking steadily rose to as high as No. 131 in the world near the end of the year. She also finished the season with eight ITF doubles titles to reach a year-end doubles ranking of No. 73.\n\n===2017: Return to top 100===\n[[File:Taylor Townsend Roland Garros 2017.jpg|thumb|Townsend at the 2017 French Open]]\nUp until the very end of the year, Townsend maintained her ranking just outside of the top 100. She reached the third round of the [[2017 Miami Open|Miami Open]] as a qualifier, her best result at a [[WTA Premier tournaments|Premier]] tier tournament to date. In the spring, Townsend had a quieter clay court season compared to the previous year, but still won a match at the [[2017 French Open|French Open]] yet again. She produced another solid performance at a premier tournament in August, making it to the second round at the [[2017 Cincinnati Masters|Cincinnati Masters]] after needing to qualify for the main draw. Towards the end of the season, she won both the singles and doubles events at back-to-back tournaments for the second time in her career, this time at the $25K level. In her final tournament of the year, Townsend played in the [[2017 Waco Showdown|Waco Showdown]] and dominated the early rounds, losing a total of just two games in her first three matches. Townsend ended up winning this $80K event for the biggest title of her career. With this result, she also returned to the top 100.\n\n===2018: Career-high ranking===\nIn the spring, Townsend delivered an exemplary performance during the American ITF clay court season. She reached the semifinals at two out of the four events ([[2018 Space Coast Pro Tennis Classic|Indian Harbour Beach]] and [[2018 Boyd Tinsley Clay Court Classic|Charlottesville]]) and won the title at the other two tournaments ([[2018 Hardee's Pro Classic|Dothan]] and [[2018 LTP Charleston Pro Tennis|Charleston]]), both of which were $80K events. She also easily won the French Open Wildcard Challenge for the third time in her career. At the end of this stretch of events, Townsend reached a career-high ranking of No. 73 in the world.\n\nShe played for the [[Philadelphia Freedoms]] in the [[2018 World TeamTennis season|World TeamTennis]] league, where she was awarded the season's Female MVP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtt.com/news/2018-wtt-season-award-winners-townsend-matkowski|title=Townsend, Matkowski Lead 2018 WTT Award Recipients|website=World TeamTennis|date=3 August 2018}}</ref> The team lost in the WTT Finals.\n\n===2019: First top 10 win===\nAt the [[2019 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|US Open]], Townsend achieved her first victory against a top 10 player, upsetting world No. 4 [[Simona Halep]] in a third-set tiebreaker in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/29/us/us-open-taylor-townsend-upsets-simona-halep-spt-intl-trnd/index.html|title=Who is Taylor Townsend, the 23-year-old American who upset Simona Halep?|website=CNN|date=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2012 US Open controversy==\nTownsend was asked by the [[USTA]] to sit out of the 2012 US Open Junior tournament due to her weight and also denied her request for a wild card for the US Open main draw or the qualifying tournament, which she had received the year before.<ref name=\"si\" /> [[Patrick McEnroe]] stated, \"Our concern is her long-term health, number one, and her long-term development as a player. We have one goal in mind: For her to be playing in Arthur Ashe Stadium in the main draw and competing for major titles when it's time.\"<ref name=\"wsj1\">{{cite web|title=Why the USTA Benched America's Best Junior|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444273704577635530959121916|work=Wall Street Journal|date=8 September 2012}}</ref> Townsend was shocked by the USTA's decision given that she was the top-ranked junior girl in the world.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite web|title=Taylor Townsend: Benched No More |url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303851804579559781715630434|work=Wall Street Journal|date=May 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe decision was sharply criticized by players like [[Lindsay Davenport]] and [[Martina Navratilova]].<ref name=davenport>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/8359772/2012-us-open-usta-handling-top-junior-taylor-townsend-causing-fits |title=USTA Handling of Top Junior Player Causing Fits |date=September 9, 2012 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' wrote, \"Instead of helping a promising young talent gain that confidence and experience gleaned from competing, the USTA has taken a paternalistic tack, deeming itself the arbiter and architect behind Townsend's past, present and future success. It's the arrogance of institution built on the belief that there is a tried-and-true formula to build a champion.\"<ref name=\"si\">{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/tennis/beyond-baseline/2012/09/07/taylor-townsend-usta-controversy |title=Taylor Townsend dispute: USTA cuts funding until No. 1 junior loses weight |date=September 7, 2012 |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe USTA at first refused to pay for Townsend's expenses,<ref name=\"wsj1\" /> so she paid to enter the tournament and was defeated in the quarterfinals by [[Anett Kontaveit]] in straight sets. Later, the USTA agreed to pay for Townsend's expenses as Patrick McEnroe spoke of a miscommunication.<ref>{{cite web|title=USTA To Pay Townsend's Expenses |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/dailyfix/2012/09/07/usta-to-pay-townsends-tennis-expenses/|work=Wall Street Journal|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> Still, the USTA decision cost Townsend an opportunity to compete for a wild card to enter the main draw of the US Open.<ref name=\"wsj\" />\n\nFollowing the controversy, Townsend split from her USTA coaches and began training with former world No. 4, Olympic doubles gold medalist, and 1990 Wimbledon finalist [[Zina Garrison]], who continued to coach her until 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zina Garrison Works With Future Tennis Star Taylor Townsend |url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303851804579559781715630434|publisher=NBC Washington|date=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"joy\">{{cite web|title=A Former Prodigy Recaptures the Joy That Made Her a Star|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/23/sports/tennis/taylor-townsend-miami-open.html|website=New York Times|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Performance timelines==\n{{Performance key}}\n===Singles===\n''Only main-draw results in WTA Tour, Grand Slam tournaments and Olympic Games are included in Win\u2013Loss records.''\n\n''This table is current through the [[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2020 Australian Open]].''\n{|class=\"wikitable nowrap\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Tournament\n! [[2011 WTA Tour|2011]]\n! [[2012 WTA Tour|2012]]\n! [[2013 WTA Tour|2013]]\n! [[2014 WTA Tour|2014]]\n! [[201