arzyna Kawa]]\n| 4\u20136, 7\u20135, [10\u20133]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n|<small>17\u20137</small>\n|[[2019 LTP Charleston Pro Tennis \u2013 Doubles|May 2019]]\n| style=\"background:#f88379;\"|[[LTP Charleston Pro Tennis|ITF Charleston]], <br/> United States\n| style=\"background:#f88379;\"|100,000\n| Clay\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Asia Muhammad\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Madison Brengle]] <br /> {{flagicon|USA}} [[Lauren Davis]]\n| 6\u20132, 6\u20132\n|}\n\n==Junior Grand Slam finals==\n===Girls' singles: 2 (1 title, 1 runner-up)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Result\n!Year\n!Tournament\n!Surface\n!Opponent\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| [[2012 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|2012]]\n| [[Australian Open]]\n| Hard\n| {{flagicon|KAZ}} [[Yulia Putintseva]]\n| 6\u20131, 3\u20136, 6\u20133\n|-style=\"background:#CCFFCC;\"\n| style=\"background:#FFA07A;\"|Loss\n| [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Singles|2013]]\n| [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}}&nbsp; [[Belinda Bencic]]\n| 6\u20134, 1\u20136, 4\u20136\n|}\n\n===Girls' doubles: 3 (3 titles)===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Result\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Surface\n! Partner\n! Opponents\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| [[2012 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2012]]\n| [[Australian Open]]\n| Hard\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Gabrielle Andrews]]\n| {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Irina Khromacheva]] <br/> {{flagicon|MNE}} [[Danka Kovini\u0107]]\n| 5\u20137, 7\u20135, [10\u20136]\n|-style=\"background:#CCFFCC;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2012]]\n| [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Eugenie Bouchard]]\n| {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Belinda Bencic]] <br /> {{flagicon|CRO}} [[Ana Konjuh]]\n| 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|-style=\"background:#b2c8ff;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| [[2012 US Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|2012]]\n| [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]\n| Hard\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Gabrielle Andrews\n| {{flagicon|SUI}} Belinda Bencic <br/> {{flagicon|SVK}} Petra Uberalov\u00e1\n| 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|}\n\n==Wins over top 10 players==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n!#\n!Player\n!Rank\n!Event\n!Surface\n!Rd\n!Score\n!{{Tooltip|TTR|Taylor Townsend Rank}}\n|-\n|colspan=8 style=text-align:center|'''[[2019 WTA Tour|2019]]'''\n|-\n| 1.\n| {{flagicon|ROU}} [[Simona Halep]]\n| bgcolor=eee8aa|No. 4\n| bgcolor=f3e6d7|[[2019 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|US Open]], United States\n| bgcolor=ccccff|Hard\n| bgcolor=afeeee|2R\n| 2\u20136, 6\u20133, 7\u20136<sup>(7\u20134)</sup>\n| No. 116\n|}\n\n===Record against top 10 players===\nTownsend's match record against players who have been ranked in the top 10.\n{{Div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* {{flagicon|GER}} [[Julia G\u00f6rges]] 2\u20130\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[CoCo Vandeweghe]] 1\u20130\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Roberta Vinci]] 1\u20130\n* {{flagicon|GER}} [[Andrea Petkovic]] 1\u20131\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Sofia Kenin]] 1\u20132\n* {{flagicon|ROM}} [[Simona Halep]] 1\u20133\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Bianca Andreescu]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Belinda Bencic]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|NED}} [[Kiki Bertens]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Caroline Garcia]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Ana Ivanovic]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Daria Kasatkina]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Svetlana Kuznetsova]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Kristina Mladenovic]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Garbi\u00f1e Muguruza]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|LAT}} [[Je\u013cena Ostapenko]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|POL}} [[Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Sloane Stephens]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Samantha Stosur]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|UKR}} [[Elina Svitolina]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Serena Williams]] 0\u20131\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Flavia Pennetta]] 0\u20132\n* {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Caroline Wozniacki]] 0\u20133\n{{div col end}}\n:''* {{as of|2020|3|9}}''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Taylor Townsend}}\n* {{WTA}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Fed Cup player}}\n*[http://www.coretennis.net/tennis-player/taylor-townsend/15798/profile.html CoreTennis profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession  box |\n | before = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Irina Khromacheva]]\n | after  = {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Belinda Bencic]]\n | title  = [[ITF World Champions#Girls' combined (from 2003)|ITF Junior World Champion]]\n | years  = 2012\n|}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Australian Open girls\u2019 singles champions}}\n{{Australian Open girls' doubles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon girls' doubles champions}}\n{{US Open girls' doubles champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Townsend, Taylor}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American female tennis players]]\n[[Category:American female tennis players]]\n[[Category:Australian Open (tennis) junior champions]]\n[[Category:US Open (tennis) junior champions]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon junior champions]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in girls' singles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in girls' doubles]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name = Taylor Townsend\n| fullname =\n| image = Townsend RG19 (29) (48199067157).jpg\n| caption = Townsend at the [[2019 French Open]]\n| country = {{USA}}\n| residence = [[Smyrna, Georgia]], United States\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1996|4|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], Illinois, United States\n| height = 1.70 m\n| turnedpro = December 2012\n| retired =\n| plays = Left-handed (two-handed backhand)\n| careerprizemoney = [[US$]] 2,164,921\n| coach = Donald Young Sr.\n| singlesrecord = {{tennis record|won=209|lost=128}}\n| singlestitles = 0\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 61 (July,16 2018)\n| currentsinglesranking = No. 73 (March,16 2020)\n| AustralianOpenresult = 2R ([[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2020]])\n| FrenchOpenresult = 3R ([[2014 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2014]])\n| Wimbledonresult = 2R ([[2018 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2018]], [[2019 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2019]])\n| USOpenresult = 4R ([[2019 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2019]])\n| doublesrecord = {{tennis record|won=158|lost=63}}\n| doublestitles = 1 \n| highestdoublesranking = No. 64 (March,20 2017)\n| currentdoublesranking = No. 84 (March,9 2020)\n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult= 3R ([[2019 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2019]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult= 2R ([[2018 French Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2018]])\n| WimbledonDoublesresult= 1R ([[2017 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|2017]])\n| USOpenDoublesresult= QF ([[2016 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2016]])\n| AustralianOpenMixedresult =\n| FrenchOpenMixedresult =\n| WimbledonMixedresult =\n| USOpenMixedresult = SF ([[2014 US Open \u2013 Mixed Doubles|2014]])\n| Team = yes\n| FedCupresult = 1\u20130\n| updated = 9 March 2020\n}}\n\n'''Taylor Townsend''' (born April 16, 1996) is an [[American people|American]] professional [[tennis]] player. She reached a career-best [[WTA Rankings|WTA]] ranking of No. 61 in July 2018.\n\nShe was named the ITF Junior World Champion in 2012 for finishing the year No. 1 in the girls' junior rankings, making her the first American to do so since 1982. In that year, she won the junior [[2012 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|Australian Open]] titles in both singles and doubles, and three out of the four junior grand slam doubles titles in total.\n\n==Early life and background==\nTaylor was born in [[Chicago]] to Devin and Sheila Townsend. Her parents are both high school administrators, and her mother used to work as a banker. Sheila played Division II tennis at [[Lincoln University (Missouri)|Lincoln University]] in Missouri. Taylor has an older sister, Symone, who played college tennis at [[Florida A&M]].<ref name=rush /><ref name=chicago />\n\nTownsend started playing tennis at the age of six, and was one of the first junior players to participate in the XS Tennis program run by [[Kamau Murray]].<ref name=\"first-murray\">{{cite web |title=The Open Interview: Kamau Murray |url=http://www.usopen.org/en_US/news/articles/2017-09-10/2017-09-10_the_open_interview_kamau_murray.html?chip=8 |website=US Open |accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref> Murray is better known for coaching [[Sloane Stephens]] to a grand slam title. When she was eight years old, she moved to Atlanta to continue training with [[Donald Young (tennis)|Donald Young]]'s father. Townsend's mother is a close friend of Donald Young Sr., as the two of them grew up together on the [[South Side of Chicago]], where they trained at the same tennis center. At age 14, Townsend moved to [[Boca Raton, Florida]], to join the USTA development program. When the USTA decided not to fund Townsend's expenses to compete at the [[2012 US Open (tennis)|2012 US Open]], Murray and XS Tennis organized a fundraiser to cover nearly $1000 of the cost of the trip. After that, Townsend split time training with Murray in Chicago and [[Zina Garrison]] in the [[Washington DC]] area. Since 2015, Donald Young Sr. has again served as her coach. Townsend tries to model her game after her tennis idol, [[Martina Navratilova]].<ref name=chicago>{{cite web|title=Tennis takes Taylor Townsend from Englewood to Paris|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-05-23/news/ct-taylor-townsend-tennis-met-0521-20140523_1_tennis-scholarship-college-scholarships-englewood|website=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=espnw>{{cite web|title=Townsend, Young share deep connection|url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/11005122/espnw-taylor-townsend-donald-young-share-deep-connection|website=espnW|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=huff>{{cite web|title= Teen Tennis Star's Success is a Powerful Argument Against Body-Shaming |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/29/taylor-townsend-french-open_n_5412657.html|date=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Junior career==\nTownsend won the [[2012 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|2012 Australian Open]] junior tournament at the age of 15 to become only the second American to ever win that title after [[Kim Kessaris]] in 1989. She also won the [[2012 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|doubles title]] at the same event to become first American to win both the singles and doubles titles at a junior Grand Slam event since [[Lindsay Davenport]] accomplished the feat at the [[1992 US Open (tennis)|1992 US Open]].<ref name=si /> A few months later, Townsend won the Easter Bowl to help complete her rise to No. 1 in the ITF junior rankings before the end of April.<ref>{{cite web|title=Florida Tennis Briefs: American Townsend Rises to No. 1 in the ITF World Junior Tennis Rankings|url=http://www.florida.usta.com/news/florida_tennis_briefs5_gainesville_jax_score_at_league_nationals_manzo_honored111/|website=USTA Florida|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Taylor Townsend (USA) Backhand.jpg|thumb|left|Townsend at [[2012 US Open (tennis)|2012 US Open]]]]\nTownsend continued her junior Grand Slam success in doubles that year by winning the [[2012 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Doubles|Junior Wimbledon]] title with [[Eugenie Bouchard]] and the [[2012 US Open \u2013 Girls' Doubles|US Open]] title with [[Gabrielle Andrews]], with whom she also partnered at the Australian Open. The only Grand Slam that eluded Townsend was the [[French Open]], where she lost in the semifinals while partnering with Bouchard. Additionally, she was able to win the US Open title in spite of being asked to sit out that tournament by the [[USTA]] over fitness concerns.<ref name=wsj1 /> This was only the seventh year where a player or team was able to win three out of four Grand Slam doubles titles, with senior Grand Slam winners [[Victoria Azarenka]] and [[Sloane Stephens]] among the others to complete this task. Townsend finished the season as the No. 1 ranked junior in the world, for which she was named the 2012 ITF Junior World Champion. She became the first American girl to hold this honor since [[Gretchen Rush]] in 1982.<ref name=rush>{{cite web|title=Being Considered the Next Serena Is a Compliment and a Detriment|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/23/sports/tennis/taylor-townsend-americas-latest-tennis-prodigy-prepares-to-turn-pro.html|website=New York Times|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nTownsend continued to play on the junior tour in 2013 and reached another Grand Slam singles final at [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Singles|Wimbledon]], this time losing to [[Belinda Bencic]]. She also competed in the USTA Junior National Championship as the No. 4 seed and was knocked out in the semifinals by No. 2 [[Allie Kiick]].\n\n==Professional career==\n===Early years: WTA doubles final===\nTownsend entered her first professional-level tournament in October 2010 at the age of 14 and was able to win her first career match. She also played in the doubles event at the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|2011 US Open]] when she was 15 years old and reached the third round with her compatriot [[Jessica Pegula]]. She also received a wild card into the singles qualifying draw and defeated world No. 122 [[Arantxa Parra Santonja]] in the first round. The following year, Townsend requested another wild card into the [[2012 US Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|2012 US Open]] and was declined due to the USTA's concerns about Townsend's fitness. The USTA received [[Taylor Townsend (tennis)#2012 US Open controversy|widespread criticism]] for this decision.<ref name=si /><ref name=wsj1 /><ref name=davenport />\n\nTownsend made her [[WTA Tour]] debut in singles at the [[2013 BNP Paribas Open|2013 Indian Wells Masters]], where she defeated [[Lucie Hradeck\u00e1]] for her first tour-level match win. Her next WTA main draw appearance came at the [[2013 Citi Open]]. Although Townsend lost in singles, she also competed in the [[2013 Citi Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|doubles event]] with [[Genie Bouchard]], her doubles partner from their Wimbledon girls' doubles title the previous summer. The duo made it all the way to the final, the first career WTA final for either player.\n\n===2014: First Grand Slam match wins===\n[[File:Taylor Townsend (15142083560).jpg|thumb|Townsend at the [[2014 Toray Pan Pacific Open]]]]\nIn back-to-back weeks in the spring, Townsend played at two clay court events on the USTA pro circuit at [[2014 Boyd Tinsley Women's Clay Court Classic|Charlottesville]] and [[2014 Audi Melbourne Pro Tennis Classic|Indian Harbour Beach]]. She won both the singles and doubles titles at each of these events, her first such ITF titles. Townsend partnered with [[Asia Muhammad]] in doubles at both tournaments. With this success, she won the USTA wild card entry into the [[2014 French Open|French Open]].<ref>{{cite web|title=18-Year-Old Taylor Townsend Secures French Open Wild Card|url=http://www.tennisnow.com/Blogs/NET-POSTS/May-2014/18-Year-Old-Taylor-Townsend-Secures-French-Open-Wi|website=Tennis Now|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> Townsend made her Grand Slam singles debut at the [[2014 French Open|French Open]] ranked No. 205 in the world. She defeated fellow American No. 65 [[Vania King]] and then upset the top-ranked French woman No. 21 [[Aliz\u00e9 Cornet]] to advance to the third round, where she lost to No. 15 [[Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro]].<ref>{{cite web|title=American tennis discovers new star in 18-year-old Taylor Townsend|url=http://www.tennisworldusa.org/tennis/news/American_Tennis/18218/american-tennis-discovers-new-star-in-18yearold-taylor-townsend/|website=Tennis World USA|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> [[Sloane Stephens]] was the only other American woman to make it that far in the tournament.\n\nTownsend also received wild cards to make her main draw debuts at the last two grand slams of the year, [[2014 Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] and the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], but lost in the first round at each tournament. The latter loss was to [[Serena Williams]], who went on to win the title.\n\n===2015: Top 100 debut, and decline===\n[[File:Townsend RG15 (5) (19120333829).jpg|thumb|left|Townsend at the [[2015 French Open]]]]\nTownsend broke into the top 100 of the WTA rankings at the very start of the season after reaching the second round at the [[2015 ASB Classic|ASB Classic]] in Auckland. With a higher ranking, she gained direct entry into the [[2014 Australian Open|Australian Open]] and lost to [[Caroline Wozniacki]] in the first round. In February, she made her [[Fed Cup]] debut against [[Argentina Fed Cup team|Argentina]] and won her only match, a [[dead rubber]] where she was partnered with [[CoCo Vandeweghe]]. Townsend then fell out of the top 100 in April and began to struggle with her form, winning just two matches on the ITF circuit the rest of the year and none at the WTA Tour level. She finished the year ranked outside of the top 300.\n\n===2016: Resurgence, ITF doubles dominance===\nWith a lower ranking, Townsend returned to playing ITF events almost exclusively. Her decision to switch back to her childhood coach, Donald Young Sr. after the 2015 French Open eventually began to pay off as she regained her form in the spring.<ref name=SIyoung>{{cite web|title=Taylor Townsend goes back to the basics after injury, coaching change|url=https://www.si.com/tennis/2015/05/26/taylor-townsend-french-open-ankle-injury-coaching-change|website=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> In April, she repeated her feat from 2014 of winning both the singles and doubles titles at [[2016 Boyd Tinsley Women's Clay Court Classic|Charlottesville]]. This again helped her win the French Open Wild Card Challenge. After partnering with Asia Muhammad just once in 2015, the previously successful doubles team recombined to win five ITF doubles titles by the end of April, including back-to-back-to-back clay court titles at Pelham, [[2016 Hardee's Pro Classic|Dothan]], and Charlottesville. Townsend returned to the Top 200 by May and got back to No. 154 after winning her first round match at the [[2016 French Open|French Open]]. From there, her ranking steadily rose to as high as No. 131 in the world near the end of the year. She also finished the season with eight ITF doubles titles to reach a year-end doubles ranking of No. 73.\n\n===2017: Return to top 100===\n[[File:Taylor Townsend Roland Garros 2017.jpg|thumb|Townsend at the 2017 French Open]]\nUp until the very end of the year, Townsend maintained her ranking just outside of the top 100. She reached the third round of the [[2017 Miami Open|Miami Open]] as a qualifier, her best result at a [[WTA Premier tournaments|Premier]] tier tournament to date. In the spring, Townsend had a quieter clay court season compared to the previous year, but still won a match at the [[2017 French Open|French Open]] yet again. She produced another solid performance at a premier tournament in August, making it to the second round at the [[2017 Cincinnati Masters|Cincinnati Masters]] after needing to qualify for the main draw. Towards the end of the season, she won both the singles and doubles events at back-to-back tournaments for the second time in her career, this time at the $25K level. In her final tournament of the year, Townsend played in the [[2017 Waco Showdown|Waco Showdown]] and dominated the early rounds, losing a total of just two games in her first three matches. Townsend ended up winning this $80K event for the biggest title of her career. With this result, she also returned to the top 100.\n\n===2018: Career-high ranking===\nIn the spring, Townsend delivered an exemplary performance during the American ITF clay court season. She reached the semifinals at two out of the four events ([[2018 Space Coast Pro Tennis Classic|Indian Harbour Beach]] and [[2018 Boyd Tinsley Clay Court Classic|Charlottesville]]) and won the title at the other two tournaments ([[2018 Hardee's Pro Classic|Dothan]] and [[2018 LTP Charleston Pro Tennis|Charleston]]), both of which were $80K events. She also easily won the French Open Wildcard Challenge for the third time in her career. At the end of this stretch of events, Townsend reached a career-high ranking of No. 73 in the world.\n\nShe played for the [[Philadelphia Freedoms]] in the [[2018 World TeamTennis season|World TeamTennis]] league, where she was awarded the season's Female MVP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtt.com/news/2018-wtt-season-award-winners-townsend-matkowski|title=Townsend, Matkowski Lead 2018 WTT Award Recipients|website=World TeamTennis|date=3 August 2018}}</ref> The team lost in the WTT Finals.\n\n===2019: First top 10 win===\nAt the [[2019 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|US Open]], Townsend achieved her first victory against a top 10 player, upsetting world No. 4 [[Simona Halep]] in a third-set tiebreaker in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/29/us/us-open-taylor-townsend-upsets-simona-halep-spt-intl-trnd/index.html|title=Who is Taylor Townsend, the 23-year-old American who upset Simona Halep?|website=CNN|date=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2012 US Open controversy==\nTownsend was asked by the [[USTA]] to sit out of the 2012 US Open Junior tournament due to her weight and also denied her request for a wild card for the US Open main draw or the qualifying tournament, which she had received the year before.<ref name=\"si\" /> [[Patrick McEnroe]] stated, \"Our concern is her long-term health, number one, and her long-term development as a player. We have one goal in mind: For her to be playing in Arthur Ashe Stadium in the main draw and competing for major titles when it's time.\"<ref name=\"wsj1\">{{cite web|title=Why the USTA Benched America's Best Junior|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444273704577635530959121916|work=Wall Street Journal|date=8 September 2012}}</ref> Townsend was shocked by the USTA's decision given that she was the top-ranked junior girl in the world.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite web|title=Taylor Townsend: Benched No More |url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303851804579559781715630434|work=Wall Street Journal|date=May 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe decision was sharply criticized by players like [[Lindsay Davenport]] and [[Martina Navratilova]].<ref name=davenport>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/8359772/2012-us-open-usta-handling-top-junior-taylor-townsend-causing-fits |title=USTA Handling of Top Junior Player Causing Fits |date=September 9, 2012 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' wrote, \"Instead of helping a promising young talent gain that confidence and experience gleaned from competing, the USTA has taken a paternalistic tack, deeming itself the arbiter and architect behind Townsend's past, present and future success. It's the arrogance of institution built on the belief that there is a tried-and-true formula to build a champion.\"<ref name=\"si\">{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/tennis/beyond-baseline/2012/09/07/taylor-townsend-usta-controversy |title=Taylor Townsend dispute: USTA cuts funding until No. 1 junior loses weight |date=September 7, 2012 |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe USTA at first refused to pay for Townsend's expenses,<ref name=\"wsj1\" /> so she paid to enter the tournament and was defeated in the quarterfinals by [[Anett Kontaveit]] in straight sets. Later, the USTA agreed to pay for Townsend's expenses as Patrick McEnroe spoke of a miscommunication.<ref>{{cite web|title=USTA To Pay Townsend's Expenses |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/dailyfix/2012/09/07/usta-to-pay-townsends-tennis-expenses/|work=Wall Street Journal|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> Still, the USTA decision cost Townsend an opportunity to compete for a wild card to enter the main draw of the US Open.<ref name=\"wsj\" />\n\nFollowing the controversy, Townsend split from her USTA coaches and began training with former world No. 4, Olympic doubles gold medalist, and 1990 Wimbledon finalist [[Zina Garrison]], who continued to coach her until 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zina Garrison Works With Future Tennis Star Taylor Townsend |url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303851804579559781715630434|publisher=NBC Washington|date=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"joy\">{{cite web|title=A Former Prodigy Recaptures the Joy That Made Her a Star|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/23/sports/tennis/taylor-townsend-miami-open.html|website=New York Times|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Performance timelines==\n{{Performance key}}\n===Singles===\n''Only main-draw results in WTA Tour, Grand Slam tournaments and Olympic Games are included in Win\u2013Loss records.''\n\n''This table is current through the [[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2020 Australian Open]].''\n{|class=\"wikitable nowrap\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Tournament\n! [[2011 WTA Tour|2011]]\n! [[2012 WTA Tour|2012]]\n! [[2013 WTA Tour|2013]]\n! [[2014 WTA Tour|2014]]\n! [[2015 WTA Tour|2015]]\n! [[2016 WTA Tour|2016]]\n! [[2017 WTA Tour|2017]]\n! [[2018 WTA Tour|2018]]\n! [[2019 WTA Tour|2019]]\n! [[2020 WTA Tour|2020]]\n! {{Abbr| SR | Strike Rate}}\n! {{Abbr| W\u2013L | Win\u2013Loss}}\n! Win %\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" align=\"left\" |'''Grand Slam tournaments'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Australian Open]]\n|A\n|A\n|A\n|A\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2015 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n|A\n|style=\"background:#ecf2ff\"|[[2017 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles Qualifying|Q3]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|